<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BanishedBear     05-15 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banished Bear,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banished Pet Bear Leaves Suburban Home For Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thor, a 450-pound pet bear who wasn't
wanted in the suburbs, has moved to the country.
   Sunday was the deadline Bloomington officials had given Thor's
owners, Charles and Deborah Crosby, to move the bear from his
backyard home in the Minneapolis suburb. Officials had cited a city
ordinance prohibiting wild animals.
   Thor was moved quietly Friday night to a new home the couple
built on 12 acres outside of city limits, Crosby's mother said
Sunday.
   ``We miss him terribly,'' said Walterine Crosby, who referred to
herself as Thor's ``grandma.''
   The bear's new den is made of earth-banked logs and features a
40-foot by 40-foot cage and a pond near the Crosby's new home. The
nearest neighbors are miles away.
   The Bloomington City Council first tried to banish Thor last
fall after someone called City Hall to report the bear. Officials
ordered the Crosbys to get rid of Thor, but the order was delayed
because the bear was hibernating in a fenced-in den and nobody
wanted to wake him up.
   The Crosbys, who got Thor as a 5-week-old cub from a game farm,
have said the now 3-year-old bear has never hurt anyone, his front
claws have been removed and he's been trained to respond to the
command, ``Don't touch.''
</TEXT>
