<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Venice-Sea     05-15 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Venice-Sea,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venice Celebrates Link to Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE,Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a ritual that began nearly 1,000 years
ago, the mayor of Venice renewed the city's links to the sea with
fanfare and festivities.
   Mayor Antonio Casellati, accompanied by other dignitaries, were
in a procession of boats that went from St. Mark's Square to the
port of St. Nicolo del Lido.
   Casellati then blessed a ring and a laurel wreath and cast them
into the sea, repeating the words of the ancient rite: ``As a sign
of eternal dominance, we marry you, oh sea.''
   The ceremony was first performed in 997 when the forces of Doge
Pietro Orseolo II, the chief magistrate of the republic of Venice,
conquered Dalmatia, a province of Croatia. The ritual was then
repeated every year until 1797 when Napoleon canceled the ceremony
after his troops conquered the area.
</TEXT>
