<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0831 05-15 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0831,0512</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Emmerich death. An AM separate moved on Emmerich, a0837.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Sergei Gorshkov</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Admiral Sergei Gorshkov, the man credited with
turning the Soviet Union into a modern naval power, died Friday at
age 78, Tass said.
   Gorshkov was appointed to head the Soviet navy in 1956 by Nikita
S. Khrushchev, who considered Josef Stalin's emphasis on large
surface vessels impractical because of their vulnerability to
rocket attacks.
   In the book ``Sea Power of the State,'' Gorshkov said the Soviet
navy's development of a fleet of submarines and missile-launching
warships had frustrated ``illusory hopes of imperialist aggressors
that in the sphere of armed conflict at sea they would have no
strong opponent.''
   Gorshkov was replaced in 1985.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Arthur S. Miller</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur S. Miller, who was chief legal
consultant to the chairman of the Senate Watergate investigations,
died Friday of a brain tumor at his home in Key West, Fla. He was
71.
   Miller was on the George Washington University law faculty in
1950 and from 1961 until he retired in 1978. He had also taught at
Emory University in Atlanta, Ga., and wrote or edited 15 books on
constitutional law.
   Miller was chief consultant for the late Sen. Sam Ervin, D-N.C.,
chairman of the investigations that led to President Richard
Nixon's resignation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Zambelli</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Zambelli, the Grandfather of
Fireworks whose pyrotechnics lit up the sky at presidential
inaugurations and the Statue of Liberty's centennial in 1986, died
Thursday at age 80.
   Zambelli was vice president of production at Zambelli
International America, the business founded by his Italian
immigrant father.
   Zambelli put together displays for six U.S. presidents,
including fireworks at the inaugurations of Jimmy Carter and Ronald
Reagan. His fireworks also have been used at a welcome home party
for American hostages held in Iran and a salute to Pope John Paul
II.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John B. Garrison</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John B. Garrison, a former hockey star at
Harvard who played for the U.S. Olympic team in the 1930s and
coached the 1948 Olympic squad, died Friday at age 79.
   After graduating from Harvard in 1931, Garrison played for the
U.S. team that won a silver medal at the 1932 Olympics in Lake
Placid, N.Y. He also played for the 1936 team, which won the
bronze.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert D. Emmerich</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUDERDALE LAKES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert D. Emmerich, who played
piano with the Tommy Dorsey band and wrote songs for Fats Waller,
died Friday at age 83.
   Emmerich wrote more than 100 songs, including ``Beat It Out,''
``Woe Is Me'' and 10 others for Waller. He wrote ``Our Love,''
first sung by Dinah Shore, and ``No. 10 Lullaby Lane,'' introduced
by Kate Smith.
   Emmerich wrote a song called ``The Big Apple'' in the 1940s,
said his wife, Miriam. The columnist Walter Winchell ``liked it so
much he started calling New York `the Big Apple,''' she said.
</TEXT>
