<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Cuomo 1stLd-Writethru a0666 05-15 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Governor Calls Dukakis Likely Nominee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with Cuomo comments on Bush at later
appearance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Saturday it
appears Michael Dukakis will win the Democratic presidential
nomination, but the party will need the aid of Jesse Jackson and
his supporters to win in November.
   ``A Jesse Jackson who is an impassioned part of the effort to
support Mike Dukakis if Mike wins, and that's the way it looks,
that would be helpful, absolutely,'' Cuomo said at a news
conference following a speech to the World Affairs Council of
Oregon.
   Cuomo stopped short of endorsing Dukakis, although he promised
to come out in favor of the race's front-runner before the
convention.
   ``I have great respect for this process,'' he said. ``I will not
treat this as a make-believe race.''
   At the news conference and during a question-and-answer session
with the audience after his speech, Cuomo said the people who are
supporting Jackson's campaign need to be convinced that Jackson is
not the only politician who shares their concerns.
   He said he met with Jackson for more than an hour Friday in
California to discuss that issue.
   The Democratic Party must assure Jackson supporters ``that Jesse
isn't the only one who is concerned about the drug problem,
concerned about education, concerned about corporations that leave
this country to manufacture in foreign lands using cheap labor.
   ``We have to prove to his constituency that we're concerned
about a deteriorating infrastructure and that we have a way to
raise up funds to deal with it. We're concerned about a society
where rich people have gone from a 70 percent tax down to a 28
percent tax at the same time that you have the largest deficit
known in the history of the nation.''
   During his question-and-answer session with the World Affairs
Council audience, he spent several minutes explaining why he
decided not to seek the presidency. Mainly, he said, he couldn't
run for president and continue as governor of New York.
   Explaining why Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, could find
time to run, Cuomo said, ``In his state, people are baptized
Democrats. He can go out and campaign and his agenda will be taken
care of.''
   ``If I leave (New York) for very long, somebody will steal my
desk,'' he said.
   Later Saturday at a GOP fund-raiser in Seattle, Cuomo taunted
Bush for keeping quiet during the Reagan administration and called
on the vice president to explain his plans for the federal budget.
   Republicans ``would like us to think they have chosen George
Bush so early because they want to speak in one voice. I think it's
because they have nothing to say,'' Cuomo said. ``When the vice
president finally does decide to use that voice I hope he tells us
why he hasn't used that voice for eight years.''
</TEXT>
