<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Indians,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Rebels, Sadinistas Fail To Reach Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian rebels and government officials
ended six days of talks Saturday without reaching the peace
agreement they had sought for the country's Atlantic coast region.
   Uriel Vanegas, an Indian military leader, said the two sides had
reached ``a gentleman's agreement to continue the conversations
soon.
   ``The hope is in the future,'' he said.
   But Jose Gonzalez, one of the government delegates, blamed the
lack of progress on what he said were the unyielding positions of
Brooklyn Rivera, a leader of Yatama, the organization of Miskito,
Sumo and Rama Indians that met with the government.
   The organization, which claims to have 2,000 guerrillas, is not
allied with the Nicaraguan Resistance, the umbrella group for most
of the U.S.-backed rebels fighting since 1981 to overthrow the
Sandinista government.
   The Indian group wants to maintain its traditional tribal
boundaries, elect its own officials and preserve its customs.
   During the negotiations, Rivera maintained his positions on
boundaries, autonomy for the Atlantic coast, a permanent cease-fire
and food assistance for 256 Indian communities in the region. Each
side accused the other of refusing to compromise.
   Rivera was quoted by local newspapers Friday as saying the
government was requiring a permanent cease-fire as a condition for
allowing the rebel leaders to visit the coast and called it
blackmail.
   He said the trip was needed to confirm signatures on documents
by some Yatama commanders.
   Steadman Fagoth Muller, another leader in the rebel delegation,
said any agreement with the government must be based on ``a
legitimate, genuine and true autonomy that effectively contemplates
the historic revindications and emancipation of the Indian people.''
   Before the talks began, Rivera said Yatama sought the dialogue
because of a cut in U.S. aid and a hostile attitude by Honduras,
which borders Nicaragua.
   The Atlantic coast Indians began fighting in 1981 after the
leftist government tried to impose authority on the isolated,
traditionally independent, region.
</TEXT>
