<2ND_LINE>AM-Firestone Strike, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0707,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Workers Strike in Six States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``These are ...,'' to
ADD Firestone comment; Inserts one graf after 8th graf pvs, ``The
URW ...,'' to add that no plants in operation; CLARIFIES lead and
8th graf to reflect plants and offices affected, ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Rubber Workers union members at
Firestone Inc. plants and offices in six states went on strike
Sunday after negotiators failed to reach a tentative agreement on a
contract settlement.
   ``They did not meet the pattern settlement negotiated with
Goodyear,'' said URW President Milan Stone after the 12:01 a.m.
Sunday deadline. Stone confirmed the strike was under way.
   Stone was referring to a tentative agreement reached by the
URW's international committee with Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. The
union intended for the agreement to serve as a pattern for other
rubber companies.
   Stone said Firestone's latest proposal did not match the pattern
settlement in the areas of pension, cost-of-living increases and
health insurance.
   ``These are the three issues that are very dear to our hearts,
and we will fight to keep those and that's why we're on strike.''
   But Firestone officials had a different view of the proposal.
   ``We are deeply distressed that the union has taken this
action,'' George W. Aucott, Firestone's executive vice president,
said in a statement. ``We believe that our proposal contains a
number of improvements, and in terms of Firestone's position in the
industry, is equal in value and in cost to the URW settlement
proposal.''
   The URW represents about 4,700 workers at Firestone plants in
Noblesville, Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.; Russellville,
Ark.; and Oklahoma City, Okla.; and offices in Akron.
   Firestone spokesman Jim Strandberg said none of the plants was
scheduled to be operating early Sunday morning.
   Talks resumed late Saturday in a final effort to avert a strike.
But even as the Firestone negotiations continued, the fate of the
pact with Goodyear was riding on the outcome of a vote Sunday by a
1,668-member local in Danville, Va.
   Goodyear's 15,000 URW members rejected the tentative contract by
a 3-1 ratio May 1. Local 831 in Danville was to vote on whether to
reconsider the pact. The vote could be pivotal because the Danville
local has enough members to turn the vote around.
   Six of the 11 Goodyear locals approved the pact, but they do not
represent a majority of the Goodyear membership in the URW. Under
URW bylaws, ratification must be made by a majority of the locals
representing a majority of the membership.
   Goodyear Chairman Robert Mercer was in Danville on Friday to
appeal to union leaders. Mercer said he met for more than an hour
with about 15 members of the local's executive board ``to urge them
to talk to their people on the floor and seek ratification.'' He
said the visit and appeal were unique in his experience as chairman.
   ``I felt it (the visit) was necessary to make sure I fulfilled
my obligations. I can't sit here in Akron and keep my fingers
crossed and hope everything goes down all right,'' he said.
   If Danville members approve a second vote, they will cast their
ballots Monday, said Local 831 Vice President Johnny Gauldin. On
May 1, 1,400 members of the Danville local rejected the pact by
nearly a 9-1 ratio.
   If Danville rejects a second vote or turns down the contract
again, the URW will strike Goodyear at noon Tuesday, officials said.
   Goodyear workers at Local 2 in Akron, who approved the pact May
1, are awaiting a vote by members of the Danville local before
holding a strike vote at the plant gates Monday. Local 2 President
Bill Breslin has urged his local's 1,700 members to keep working
even if the other locals strike.
</TEXT>
