<HEAD>Tident Missile Launch Seen Hundreds of Miles Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT MUGU NAVAL AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unarmed Trident
missile was launched from a submarine off the California coast
Saturday night, creating a brilliant streak of light visible for
hundreds of miles.
   The 8:50 p.m. launch was seen by residents throughout California
and as far inland as Las Vegas, Nev.
   ``We didn't have any obvious problems,'' said Ray Lucasey,
spokesman at the U.S. Pacific Missile Test Center.
   The target of the missile, which has the capacity of carrying
independently targeted nuclear warheads, was not identified. The
missile test range covers 35,000 square miles in the Pacific Ocean.
   ``That's about as specific we can get for security reasons,''
Lucasey said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration was forewarned about the
launch so as to clear private and commercial flights from the
launch area, said Dick Tornquist, an FAA duty officer in Los
Angeles.
   An official at the Oakland International Airport tower said a
bright, white streak was reportedly seen about 180 miles south of
San Francisco Bay area.
   Radio stations throughout the state were flooded with calls from
excited observers.
   Motorists pulled off the road in Yolo County 400 miles north of
Los Angeles to watch the aerial display, according to Woodland
Daily Democrat city editor Dave Haerle, who described the sight as
a ``star burst.''
   One witness, Steve Severano of Woodside, Calif., said the
contrail-like display looked copper-white in color, a brilliant
streak that seemed to explode as it crossed the sky in a trail of
vapors. Donna Larosa of Lafayette, Calif., said, ``There was a main
beam, then vapors.''
</TEXT>
