<HEAD>Sixth Tanker Reported Hit; Fire Doused On World's Largest Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Sunday said its war planes hit a
supertanker in the Persian Gulf, the sixth vessel Iraq has attacked
in two days of raids on Iranian oil shipping.
   Iraq said Sunday that its planes hit a ``very large maritime
target,'' a usual refernce to a supertanker, in a nighttime raid
off Iran.
   An unnamed military spokesman told the official Baghdad Radio
that planes scored ``an accurate and effective hit on the target.''
He gave no other details.
   The claim could not be immediately confirmed.
   The report of the attack came after five tankers, including the
world's largest ship, were set ablaze during a raid on one of
Iran's offshore oil terminals Saturday near Larak Island in the
Strait of Hormuz.
   Gulf-based marine salvage executives on Sunday reported an
unspecified number of crewmen were rescued after the Saturday raid
and said 4 or 5 others were missing and believed dead.
   The executives dismissed as exaggerated previous reports by a
London-based maritime agency that 54 people were missing.
   Dubai-based shipping sources said one of Saturday's victims near
Larak Island, the Spanish tanker Barcelona, was beached by salvage
tugboats and was no longer in danger of sinking. But they said
fires aboard were still blazing at dawn.
   Fires were doused on the 564,739-ton Liberian-flag Seawise
Giant, the largest vessel afloat, and the 152,004-ton Cypriot-flag
Argosy, gulf shipping sources said.
   ``The fires have been extinguished on Seawise Giant and Argosy,
but the two tankers were badly damaged in the air attack,'' said
one shipping agent.
   Also damaged were the British-flagged Burmah Endeavour, the
Cypriot-flagged Argosy and the Iranian tanker Khark, shipping
sources said.
   The Seawise Giant and the 457,841-ton Burmah Endeavour, also one
of the world's five-largest ships, are under charter to Iran as
offshore storage tankers at Larak.
   The 152,004-ton Argosy also is under Iranian charter and the
231,712-ton Khark is government owned.
   The attacks were part of an intensified effort by Baghdad to cut
off the export revenues that Tehran uses to finance the war with
Iraq, now in its eighth year.
</TEXT>
