<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 125 Sikh men left the Golden Temple
and surrendered to Indian security forces Sunday after police
unleashed a barrage of gunfire on the holy shrine.
   One of the militants who surrendered told reporters that between
40 and 45 Sikhs remained holed up in the temple complex, which has
been under siege by India government forces since Monday.
   The surrender came after the 2,800 police and paramilitary
troops around the shrine fired on the temple for an hour, then
announced a cease-fire at 11 a.m. (1 :30 a.m. EDT).
   Using bullhorns, they urged the militants to give themselves up.
Some militants fired sporadically as the Sikhs walked out of the
besieged temple, but no one was injured in the shooting, police
said.
   Punjab Police Chief K.P.S. Gill said some of those who
surrendered where seen throwing weapons into debris scattered
inside the temple complex before emerging.
   ``Until proof to the contrary, everyone will be treated as a
terrorist or an associate,'' Gill said.
   Security sources, who insisted on anonymity, said that Surjit
Singh Penta, who is wanted in connection with the shooting deaths
of more than 30 people in New Delhi last year, was believed to be
among those who surrendered.
   The United News of India news agency reported that Penta was
hospitalized in critical condition after he apparently took a
cyanide capsule following his surrender. The militants have in the
past taken poison to escape capture.
   At least 30 people, most of them Sikhs, have been killed since
the siege began Monday, when Sikh separatists inside the temple
complex opened fire and wounded five officers of the Central
Reserve Police Force.
   The Golden Temple is the spiritual center of Sikhism and its
holiest shrine.
   Sikhs comprise 2 percent of India's 800 million people, but they
are a majority in Punjab state and are fighting for an independent
Punjab homeland.
   The radicals have killed about 960 people so far this year in
Punjab, compared with 1,030 for all of 1987. The victims include
moderate Sikhs as well as Hindus.
</TEXT>
