<HEAD>Soviet Troops Begin Afghanistan Retreat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `The convoy...' to CORRECT Jalalabad-Kabul
distance. INSERTS two grafs after 6th pvs, `Information about...'
to UPDATE with quotes from U.S. official. Pick up 7th pvs, `The
Jalalabad...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 Soviet troops lumbered
into Kabul in tanks and armored personnel carriers Sunday in the
first troop movement of the retreat from the Afghan war.
   After a daylong ride through guerrilla-infested mountains, the
soldiers in the 300-vehicle convoy were greeted by cheering Afghans
who lined the streets of Kabul, turning the military movement into
a parade. Afghan President Najib was on hand to review the
departing troops.
   The convoy had pulled up stakes in Jalalabad early Sunday and
covered the 88-mile distance to the capital by evening.
   The convoy had pulled up stakes in Jalalabad in eastern
Afghanistan early Sunday and covered the 60-mile distance to the
capital by evening.
   Soviet Col. Alexander Zubrilin told reporters that there had
been no casualties during the trek through among the rough terrain
that is within the reach of U.S.-backed rebels fighting Najib's
communist government.
   Information about the start of the withdrawal was provided by a
Reuters news agency pool report. The Associated Press was barred
from covering the event, and Soviet officials said the exclusion
was the result of questions asked by the AP during a previous trip
to Kabul.
   Edmund McWilliams, deputy chief-of-mission at the U.S. Embassy
in Kabul, told The Associated Press by telephone that the rebels
have moved in closer to the capital and stepped up attacks on the
city.
   ``We've had, as you may know, this past week, quite a bit of
rocketing of the city, and we're expecting possibly some more
rocketing tonight,'' McWilliams said. ``It does not appear, though,
at this point that the attacks ... will be affecting the pullout.''
   The Jalalabad convoy was to head north on Monday along the route
that passes through the Salang Tunnel, under the Hindu Kush
mountains, to the border with Soviet Uzbekistan.
   About 115,000 Soviet troops are in Afghanistan to bolster
Najib's forces, but all must pull back to Soviet territory within
the next nine months to comply with U.N.-mediated peace accords
signed in Geneva last month.
   Half of the troops must leave by Aug. 15 under the agreement.
Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov told reporters Saturday that about one
quarter of the soldiers would be home before President Reagan
visits Moscow on May 29.
   The Communist Party leadership in Moscow headed by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev addressed the departing troops with words of thanks and a
call for the ir help in improving Soviet life once they are back on
native ground.
   ``Days of severe trials lie behind you,'' said the party Central
Committee address, printed on the front page of the party daily
Pravda. ``Your profound faith in the noble cause of assistance to
the friendly people braced you up in those trials. You have
fulfilled the order of your homeland.''
   After stating that those killed in Afghanistan would never be
forgotten, Pravda turned to the soldiers' tasks for the future.
   ``Your energy is needed today for perestroika, for the cause of
renovating socialism, for the protection of its achievements,'' the
address continued. ``The party believes in you and calls you into
the forefront of the drive for revolutionary transformations of
Soviet society.''
   Perestroika, or rebuilding, is Gorbachev's drive to shape the
nation into a more democratic and economically viable society.
   The official Tass news agency announced early Sunday that the
pullout had begun from Jalalabad with the departure of a motorized
rifle regiment.
   Tass also reported that Najib sent a message of thanks to
Gorbachev on Sunday, praising the ``heroic feat'' of the Soviets in
helping defe nd his government.
   In a joint Soviet-Afghan statement carried by Tass, the allied
governments said the ``pivotal issue'' in ending the civil war that
has gripped Afghanistan for a decade would be ensuring an end to
``interference from the outside in the home affairs of the
Afghans.''
   Soviet and Afghan officials have accused the United States and
Pakistan of exacerbating the war by delivering arms to the rebels.
   It was not clear whether other Soviet units also left their
bases on Sunday, or when the first troops would cross the border
into the Soviet Union.
   Soviet troops and tanks moved into Afghanistan on Dec. 27, 1979.
</TEXT>
