<1ST_LINE>u a BC-BusCrash 6thLd-Writethru a0727 05-15 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bus Crash, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0727,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 26 Reported Killed In Fiery Bus Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The gutted...', to CORRECT wreckage to
records.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pickup truck traveling in the wrong
direction plowed into a church bus loaded with teen-agers returning
from an amusement park late Saturday, and at least 26 people were
killed in the fiery crash, police said.
   ``I just heard a crash, felt the impact of the car (truck) and
looked up and saw flames,'' said Wayne Cox, 14, whose hair was
singed by the flames.
   ``They spread pretty fast. ... I was pinned. Everything was
pretty wild. I was under a lot of people. That's probably what
saved me from getting burned,'' said Cox, an asthmatic who suffered
smoke inhalation.
   Between 30 and 40 people were injured in the 10:55 p.m. accident
in this northern Kentucky community, police said. Among the injured
was the truck driver, who was in critical condition; at least six
others were also listed in critical condition.
   Trooper Jim Mudd, a state police spokesman, gave the number of
dead as at least 26 and said the final toll could be one or two
more.
   The worst bus accident in U.S. history occurred in Kentucky in
March, 1958, when a school bus plunged into a river, killing 26
students and the bus driver.
   The gutted wreckage, shrouded in a tarp, was brought to the
National Guard armory in Carrollton with the bodies still inside.
Officials spent Sunday morning examining the bodies but did not
immediately remove them from the wreckage. Meanwhile, relatives
were summoned to Carrolton and asked to bring dental records.
   ``This is a horrible task for anyone who cares for human life
... for such a joyous occasion to end in such sad tragedy,'' Mudd
said.
   The only listing of people on board the bus was burned in the
accident, he said, but the number was believed to be 67.
   ``They had tried to escape,'' Carroll County Coroner Jim Dunn
said. ``They were in the hallway trying to escape. Bodies were
piled on top of each other.'' The bodies were burned beyond
recognition, he said, and it would probably take hours for them to
be all removed from the wreckage.
   ``Apparently, the gas tank ruptured, throwing fuel into the
bus,'' Dunn said. He called the accident ``the worse I've ever
seen'' in his nine years as coroner.
   One passenger, Jason Booher, said the bus had refueled shortly
before the accident.
   The bus, from the First Assembly of God Church in Radcliff, was
returning to Hardin County, south of Louisville, from the King's
Island amusement park north of Cincinnati, Ohio, police said.
   The pickup was traveling northbound in the southbound lanes of
Interstate 71 when it collided head-on with the bus, Mudd said.
   A spokeswoman at the church said that the Army provided vans to
carry relatives to the temporary morgue at Carrollton.
   ``We have been asking the families to bring along any dental
records or other medical histories they may have. They've also been
asked to try to remember what the children were wearing,'' said the
spokeswoman, who declined identification.
   Survivors said that after the impact, the front of the bus burst
into flames and the fire spread quickly. Survivors escaped through
the back door and windows, said Cox.
   Booher, 13, said he and another youth helped evacuate the
passengers from the burning bus.
   Booher said he pulled survivors on to the ground outside the
back door while Jamie Hardesty stood just inside the door and
pushed them out.
   ``Jamie, he pushed everyone out,'' Booher said. ``He was up in
the bus and I was out the back door of the bus, helping those who
were hurt.''
   Booher said Jamie played ``a big part. He saved a lot.''
   Many of the parents of the youths gathered at the Radcliff
church early Sunday to await news.
   ``We're praying for each other and we're trusting the Lord,''
said Vicki Fischel, a parent of a teen-ager on the bus.
   Some of the injured were taken to Humana Hospital-University of
Louisville and Kosair Children's Hospital in Louisville. Others
were taken to Carroll County Memorial Hospital in Carrollton and
Tri-Counties Hospital in LaGrange.
   Humana nursing supervisor Kelly Moriarty said the injured were
being treated for severe burns and multiple injuries.
   Among those being treated at Humana was the truck driver, Larry
W. Mahoney, 34, of Worthville in Carroll County, Mudd said. Mudd
said Mahoney was in critical condition.
   About 24 youths initially were taken to Carroll County Memorial
Hospital, said Dr. Jeff Campbell, the emergency room physician.
Campbell said doctors in the small, 54-bed hospital had to treat
the teen-agers in the emergency room, the recovery room and the
cafeteria.
   Dr. Donald Thomas, chairman of emergency medicine at Humana
Hospital, said most of the injured were suffering from burns and
appeared to be youngsters between 15 and 16 years old.
</TEXT>
