<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AnimalCharities Bjt   05-15 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Animal Charities, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legacies From Elderly Women Enrich British Animal Charities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The monkeys at Paignton Zoological and Botanical
Gardens are soon to get new, improved housing, thanks to a $750,000
bequest from a woman who loved their company.
   For decades, elderly women have been leaving their fortunes to
animal charities like the Cats Protection League, the Donkey
Sanctuary or zoos like Paignton in southwest England.
   This week the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals received the largest gift in its 164-year history _ $5.15
million from an 80-year-old widow who lived with her cat, Pussy.
Even in a nation of pet owners, charities say, such women shine.
   Feeling alone in the world except for their pets, elderly women
are the lifeblood of Britain's multimillion-dollar animal charities.
   ``Animal charities are on the crest of a demographic boom,''
says Jonathan Clark, appeals officer for 91-year-old pet charity
Blue Cross, which in 1986 received more than half its $4.65 million
of income from bequests.
   ``Most of our supporters are of a generation whose husbands, or
potential husbands, went off to two world wars and never came back.
The last thing in their lives was a cat or a dog, and they've got
no one to leave (everything) to,'' he said.
   Women usually live longer than men, says Paul Wright, legacy
officer for the People's Dispensary for Sick Animals, founded in
1917 to treat poor peoples' pets. ``Very often they are simply left
with an animal.''
   Often, the only condition is that the charity care for their
cat, dog, even chicken. The RSPCA has received 20 cats this year,
and the dispensary was left money to subsidize a tortoise in what
Wright chuckles will be a ``long-term arrangement,'' given their
lifespans.
   The most spectacular bequests usually fall to the RSPCA,
Britain's 10th largest charity and the country's largest
animals-only cause. Last year, it depended on posthumous gifts for
nearly 70 percent of its $34.2 million income.
   ``Without that source, we wouldn't be able to function,'' said
spokeswoman Amanda Aviss.
   In 1985, its second-largest windfall came from an elderly woman
who gave $2.45 million, provided it was spent on the society's 240
inspectors who investigate cases of cruelty.
   Dorothy Walker's bequest to the RSPCA was unconditional and did
not even mention Pussy, whom the society is resettling.
   ``She often said she preferred animals to people, and she was
determined to prove it to the last,'' London's Today newspaper
quoted Mrs. Walker's former housekeeper as saying.
   Ivy Warr, an elderly woman who said she was Mrs. Walker's
sister, said she was ``shocked and disgusted'' by the will but
couldn't afford to contest.
   With large bequests, ``you'll often find relatives pop up and
try to get the money,'' acknowledges Ms. Aviss, saying the society
can only ``abide by the law.''
   But most benefactors don't hate people, charities say.
   Clark says he sometimes receives a letter saying, ``I've lost
faith in human nature. All my money can go to the animals.''
   Many elderly women have ample estates because the value of their
house has skyrocketed over the years, charities say.
   Some charities worry about depending on bequest. While human
causes also depend on them, most have far fewer bequests in
proportion to their total income.
   ``You need good live donators,'' says Elizabeth Svendsen, whose
Donkey Sanctuary depends on legacies for more than half its
voluntary income.
   ``I love the legacies, but I think it's a healthy sign to have
other donors,'' she says.
   Still, some animal lovers bypass charities, leaving money to
their own animals or to those they call their own.
   Marie Lefevre, an 84-year-old widow who died two years ago, left
$754,000 to the apes she visited regularly for 20 years at Paignton.
   Mary Rosevear, a zoo official, said the money is expected this
fall and will be used to build new ape houses and refurbish others.
``She spelled out what she wanted,'' said Mrs. Rosevear.
</TEXT>
