<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-ZeroTolerance Bjt   05-15 0991</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Zero Tolerance, Bjt,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Seizures: Interdiction or Overkill?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government calls it ``zero tolerance,''
but industry and civil liberties groups have begun to question
whether ``overkill'' isn't an equally accurate description of the
policy under which luxury yachts and other private property is
being seized in the battle against drugs.
   In the latest episode, the U.S. Coast Guard confiscated on
Saturay the yacht Monkey Business, the charter vessel that once
ferried presidential contender Gary Hart and model Donna Rice to
the Bahamas, after officers said they found 1 gram _ or one
twenty-eighth of an ounce _ of marijuana aboard.
   Only days earlier, the Coast Guard seized the $2.5 million
yacht, Ark Royal, on grounds that one-tenth of an ounce of
marijuana was aboard. No one was arrested in either case.
   Even rental cars and leased boats and trucks are being seized by
U.S. Customs Service agents and the Coast Guard, triggering
complaints from owners who argue that they shouldn't be penalized
for the acts of their customers.
   Richard Schwartz, president of the Boat Owners Association of
the United States, personally protested to the commandant of the
Coast Guard that the seizure of the $2.5 million yacht Ark Royal
was ``overkill.''
   The association, which has 265,000 members, estimates that there
are 15 million boat owners across the country.
   ``We're concerned about the drug problem in America, but there
has to be a rule of reasonableness here,'' Michael Sciulla, the
association's vice president, said Friday.
   In the case of the Ark Royal, ``the owner of the boat was not on
board, no one was arrested as far as we can tell, there were no
large amounts of drugs found on the boat,'' Sciulla said. ``It just
doesn't seem fair that the absent owner would face forfeiture on
those grounds.''
   Three days after the controversial yacht seizure, the Coast
Guard released the Ark Royal when the Irvine, Calif., owner of the
133-foot yacht paid a $1,000 fine and $600 in seizure fees. Some
marijuana seeds and two stems had been found in a dresser drawer
and a trash can aboard the boat.
   ``This type of action presents an unreasonable danger to all
boat owners for the isolated actions of passengers and crew,'' said
Michael Rogerson, president of Tomima Corp., the Ark Royal's owner.
   The government shows no signs of backing away from its new
policy. Last week, the Coast Guard seized another yacht off the
Florida coast after a search turned up a dollar bill with traces of
cocaine and a bag with marijuana residue. It also seized a 55-foot
fishing boat off San Diego after finding less than an ounce of
marijuana and a small amount of what appeared to be methamphetamine.
   Since April 11, the Coast Guard has confiscated 27 boats under
the ``Zero Tolerance'' campaign. The Customs Service is stepping up
its program, and since March 21, agents have seized 700 vehicles
containing drugs.
   ``They are not deterring bad guys, but they are punishing the
innocent guy'' with a program in which a number of rental vehicles
are being seized and held for lengthy periods, said Alan Kay,
outside general counsel to the the American Car Rental Association.
   ``One of the problems with seizure is that under any
circumstances it takes sometimes eight or nine months for the
return of the vehicle'' to a rental agency, which pays storage
costs to get it back, Kay said.
   Mary Coombs, a Miami representative of the American Civil
Liberties Union, agrees that it is excessive ``to take somebody's
property from them for something they probably couldn't control.
... It's putting people at enormous risk with no very effective way
of protecting themselves.''
   The term ``zero tolerance'' originated last year when U.S.
Attorney Peter Nunez of San Diego, Calif., and U.S. Customs Service
agents began arresting motorists carrying even tiny amounts of
drugs across the border. The Customs agents and Nunez were
embarking on an effort that has become a model for the federal
government's current war on drug users.
   Under the San Diego operation, an average of 15 people a week
are charged with drug possession, many of whom are first-time
offenders who wind up on probation for one year.
   ``I encourage federal prosecutors nationwide to emulate the
program in San Diego with all available prosecution resources,''
Attorney General Edwin Meese III said in a March 30 memo to all
U.S. attorneys.
   Meese noted that the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 includes a
$1,000 mandatory minimum fine for possession and that federal civil
asset forfeiture provisions permit law enforcement officers to
confiscate any vehicle carrying drugs, even in trace amounts.
   ``When used judiciously,'' Meese said in the memo, ``these
sanctions send present and potential users a clear signal about the
unacceptability of drug use.''
   ``The Reagan administration's view is that possession is a very
serious thing and that it's the possession of the drug which needs
to be dealt with if we're ever going to address with the drug
problem in a serious way,'' said Justice Department spokesman Terry
Eastland. ``What puts bite into our entire user prosecution
initiative is this forfeiture aspect.''
   Drug traffickers frequently are the target of asset forfeiture
proceedings, while users seldom have been. But under federal law on
civil asset forfeiture, there is no distinction between the
property of drug users and drug traffickers. Forfeiture does not
depend on the quantity of drugs involved. Nor is it a legal defense
under the forfeiture law to claim that the contraband was intended
for personal use rather than commercial trafficking.
   Meese noted in his March 30 memo that ``our primary narcotics
enforcement focus at the federal level has been and will continue
to be on supply reduction.''
   But ``it is becoming increasingly apparent that a more
consistent enforcement presence on the demand side is vital to the
success of our national anti-drug program,'' Meese said in the memo.
</TEXT>
