<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Elections     05-15 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Elections,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Ready to Hit the Polls Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One week after voters swept Socialist President
Francois Mitterrand to a second seven-year term, they face yet more
campaign pledges, political decisions, and two new rounds of voting.
   Mitterrand's announcement Saturday that he had decided to
dissolve the 577-seat National Assembly and hold elections June 5
and June 12 set off a flurry of justifications, denunciations, and
scrambling for unity among conservative parties.
   Socialist leaders called the move inevitable. To conservatives,
it was proof that Mitterrand had bamboozled voters with campaign
vows to form a center-left government of national unity.
   ``Mr. Francois Mitterrand has just demonstrated that the
position he himself had defined on this subject during the
presidential campaign ... was only aimed at putting the French
people to sleep,'' said Jean-Claude Gaudin. He leads the outgoing
Assembly contingent of the center-right Union for French Democracy,
one of two leading rightist parties that hope to defeat the
Socialists in the upcoming elections.
   After campaigning on the theme of national unity and pledging to
try to work with the existing Assembly and its three-seat
center-right majority, Mitterrand changed his mind. He said he
would seek a new Assembly to try to win a majority of his own.
   The outgoing Assembly was controlled by former Premier Jacques
Chirac's conservative Rally for the Republic party and the Union
for French Democracy. Mitterrand won 54 percent of the vote in the
May 8 presidential runoff against Chirac.
   The president named Michel Rocard, a popular Socialist with wide
appeal to the center of the political spectrum, as his new premier.
But Rocard was unable to find more than token non-Socialist
representation for his government.
   ``Mr. Mitterrand ceded to double pressure, that of the Socialist
Party which dreams of regaining an absolute majority in the
National Assembly, and that of Michel Rocard who did not have the
courage to present himself before Parliament,'' said Gaudin.
   In his nationally televised address Saturday night, the
president said the opening to the center he had sought ``could not
be brought about to the extent I wished. Therefore, it was my duty
to draw the appropriate conclusions.''
   Pierre Mehaignerie, a centrist political leader who represented
a key to any alliance with the Socialists, said he was firmly
opposed to a governing agreement with the Socialists, but he also
opposed the dissolution.
   The centrists had said they would not automatically submit a
censure motion against a Rocard government but would instead judge
each Socialist bill on its merits.
   Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of the extreme right National Front,
called the new elections a Socialist ``ambush.'' Le Pen, who scored
a surprisingly high 14 percent in the first round of the
presidential election, proposed a ``united front against the
hegemony of the Socialist Party.''
   However, Jacques Toubon, secretary-general of the Rally for the
Republic, rejected that idea. He called for his party to join the
Union for French Democracy and present single candidates in each
district to strengthen their possibilities.
   The official campaign for the first round of voting opens May 22
and closes June 3.
   According to an opinion poll published Sunday in the Journal du
Dimanche, Socialists would win 41 percent of the vote, 24 percent
would go to the Rally and 15 percent to the Union. The rest would
go to minor parties.
</TEXT>
