<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Hijack     05-15 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Hijack,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Demands Taiwan Punish Hijackers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese airline official demanded that Taiwan
severely punish two men who were granted political asylum after
they hijacked a Chinese jet to Taiwan, an official report said
Sunday.
   However, Wu Rongnan, director general of Xiamen Aviation Co.,
which operated the plane, did not comment on Taiwan's refusal to
return the hijackers to China as Communist authorities had
requested.
   The two men, former air force radar operators, hijacked a Boeing
737 with 118 people on board Thursday night and forced it to fly to
Taiwan, threatening the crew with what later turned out to be a toy
gun and fake explosives.
   Taiwan, governed since 1949 by the anti-communist Nationalist
Party, returned the plane, crew and other passengers within hours.
   It gave the hijackers asylum, but the Taiwan military has
recommended they be prosecuted for endangering flight safety.
   The People's Daily on Sunday quoted Wu as telling a news
conference in coastal Xiamen, where the hijacked flight originated,
that the hijackers' use of force warranted severe punishment.
   ``Without regard to the safety of the ... Chinese and foreign
passengers, the two hijackers used force to threaten the plane's
crew and passengers and caused the plane to exceed its speed limit,
triggering violent shaking of the plane body,'' the newspaper
quoted him as saying.
   ``In order to protect the safety of the plane and passengers,
the pilot had no choice but to fly as the hijackers directed,'' he
was quoted as saying.
   Accounts in China's official media have said the hijackers,
Zhang Qingguo, 27, and Long Guiyun, 26, covered the heads of
several crew members with plastic bags and wrapped two stewardesses
in cotton curtains to stop them from signaling for help.
   The pilot, Yang Yongling, said the hijackers told him they had
guns and knives.
   The People's Daily said ``in view of the hijackers' violent
actions, Wu demanded the Taiwanese side severely punish the two
hijackers according to aviation practice.''
   Taiwan military officials have refused comment on whether Zhang
and Long will be charged with hijacking.
   If charged and convicted of the lesser crime of endangering
flight safety, they could receive a maximum of seven years in jail.
However, the presiding judge of the court in Taiwan's capital,
Taipei, said the hijackers could expect leniency.
   Taiwan officials are torn between their desire to avoid
appearing to encourage hijacking and their sympathy for the
hijackers' motives. Zhang said they acted because they ``detested
the brutality of Communism.''
   While the hijacking was in progress, the Civil Aviation
Administration of China, parent company of the Xiamen Aviation Co.,
asked Taiwan to return the hijackers. China has not repeated this
request or commented on Taiwan's refusal to comply.
   In 1986, when the pilot of a Taiwan airliner diverted his plane
to Canton and defected to China, mainland officials returned the
plane and crew but not the pilot, and did not charge him.
   That incident led to the first direct talks between mainland and
Taiwan officials since 1949.
</TEXT>
