<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Jumbo Jet Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jet bound for Tokyo made an
emergency landing 450 miles from Japan's capital Sunday after
running short of fuel over the Pacific Ocean, authorities said.
   A Transport Ministry official at Tokyo International Airport at
Narita, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Northwest's
Flight 7, a Boeing 747 with 379 passengers and 21 crew members,
reported a fuel shortage over the ocean and landed at Chitose, a
city on Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost main island.
   He said the jetliner ran low on fuel because it was flying from
Seattle to Tokyo against strong winds.
   The official said he did not know how much fuel was left when
the plane landed at Chitose.
   After refueling, the plane landed at New Tokyo International
Airport at Narita at 4:50 p.m., about two hours late.
   A Northwest Airlines official confirmed the incident but
declined to discuss the matter.
   On May 2, a United Airlines Boeing 747 en route from Los Angeles
to Tokyo with 258 people on board landed safely at Narita on one
engine after two of its engines failed over the Pacific and a third
failed as it approached the airport.
