<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CBOWoes Bjt   05-15 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBO Woes, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Budget Office Lacks Stature It Once Had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just two years ago, the Congressional Budget
Office's economic forecasts ruled Capitol Hill, and its decisions
could force the president to cut billions of dollars in federal
spending.
   But the Congress has stripped the office of important powers,
left it without a permanent director for more than a year, and
exposed the officially non-partisan agency to charges of political
tampering.
   ``CBO is disintegrating,'' said Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa.,
chairman of the House Budget Committee.
   Congress set up its own budget office a dozen years ago to
counter the power of the president's Office of Management and
Budget. In the following decade, the agency established a
reputation for non-biased and unvarnished assessments of the
federal budget and its workings in the economy.
   In December 1985, its power peaked with passage of the emergency
deficit reduction amendment known as Gramm-Rudman. The CBO was
charged with making deficit estimates that, once averaged with
White House figures, launched automatic spending cuts across the
government.
   In 1986, however, the Supreme Court found the law defective. In
rewriting the statute, Congress relegated the CBO to advisory
status.
   A House-Senate search committee, meantime, was unable to agree
on a replacement for CBO Director Rudolph G. Penner, whose
three-year term was expiring at year's end. Penner stayed on until
March 1987.
   The two sides appear farther apart than ever over choosing a
successor. Although there are many qualified candidates, each
chamber is fighting for its own choice.
   ``Personal honor is at stake,'' said one House aide involved in
the process, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., who is expected to take over the
budget committee next year, said he was concerned Congress was
ceding back to the executive branch the economic decision-making
prowess it has fought to gain.
   ``I think Congress has to be very concerned when it begins to
lose what has been an objective eye in dealing with budget
issues,'' he said. Without an officially-appointed leader to carry
the flag, the agency is ``an easier target for those who don't like
CBO's opinions,'' he said.
   The agency is already embroiled in a dispute between House
Republicans and Democrats over a bill raising the federal minimum
wage and it has been criticized by both sides.
   The Democratic-controlled House Education and Labor Committee
asked the CBO for an official estimate of the bill's cost to the
federal and local governments. Republicans opponents, meanwhile,
requested a broader assessment including effects on the nation's
economy.
   The CBO at first answered both requests in its report to the
committee. But the Democrats ordered the CBO to delete the
nationwide assessment, which concluded that 500,000 jobs would be
lost.
   Republicans charged partisan tampering, while the Democrats
accused the CBO of failing to follow strictly the committee request.
   ``We were being used as a pawn to fight the minimum wage
legislation,'' said Jim Blum, the acting director of the agency.
``I am very much concerned about what appears to be a growing
perception that we're losing our non-partisanship.''
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, senior Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee, said he was beginning to become concerned
also. He has suggested that Blum, interim director since the
beginning of this year, be made the permanent director.
   ``There must be a leader at CBO to maintain its credibility,''
agreed Gray. But the House leadership has favored other candidates.
   With neither chamber giving ground in whose prerogative it is to
choose the director, some of those involved expect the decision
will be postponed until next year. Both the House and Senate will
have new budget committee chairman then, but Panetta, the future
House chairman, said waiting could hurt.
   ``Every day that we don't have a director there (at CBO) makes
it that much tougher for whoever's appointed to restore its
credibility,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
