<DOCNO> AP880515-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-15 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reforms Approved After Government Survives Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliament on Sunday approved
economic reforms to freeze wages and open Yugoslavia to world
markets a day after the country's two most Westernized republics
tried to topple the government.
   Both chambers of parliament backed the reforms, which Premier
Branko Mikulic worked out with the International Monetary Fund.
   Mikulic outlined the economic reforms in general terms on
Saturday, when he survived calls for his government's ouster from
Slovenia and Croatia. Yugoslavia will curb its import restrictions,
open itself to world markets and give its National Bank a stronger
monetary role, he said.
   Mikulic also talked of allowing citizens to buy stock in firms
and of increasing the role of profit in production.
   He said the new measures would be harsh but warned that more
drastic reductions in real wages lay ahead if inflation exceeded
the 90 percent target. Yugoslavia's current inflation rate is 170
percent, and it has a foreign debt of $20 billion.
   Slovenia and Croatia, the most advanced of Yugoslavia's six
republics, blame Mikulic's government for the nation's economic
crisis and urged a vote of no-confidence in the government.
Parliament on Saturday decided against voting on the motion.
   During Saturday's discussion, closed to the public but reported
in detail by the state-run media, even Mikulic's supporters noted
the government had failed to master the economic crisis.
   The government's failure has eroded support for the Communist
Party, which has governed this nation since World War II.
   Serbian intellectuals and Slovenians have even begun calling
openly for a multi-party Western democracy.
   Mikulic blamed what he termed ``the antiquity, lack of
flexibility and inefficiency'' of the current economic system for
the crisis but rejected any immediate need for political reform.
   Yugoslavia's six constituent republics and two autonomous
provinces are currently battling over how to reform the country's
awkward 1974 constitution, bequeathed by the late Josip Broz Tito
in what he said was an attempt to avoid ethnic conflict.
   Mikulic said Saturday he wanted the constitutional reform pushed
through by early fall.
   The constitution has proved unworkable because of its
requirement that each republic and province approve all key
political decisions and because of its mandatory annual rotation of
all state and Communist Party offices.
   The ritual of rotating the presidency took place on Sunday, with
former Foreign Minister Raif Dizdarevic, a Bosnian, taking over
from Lazar Mojsov, a Macedonian.
   Yugoslavia is hoping to get $2 billion of debt payments
rescheduled and to receive another $1.4 billion from the IMF later
this month.
   Agreement with the IMF had been expected last week, but the fund
apparently delayed approval pending this weekend's confidence vote
on the Mikulic government.
   Yugoslavia is also expected to secure $300 million in bridging
loans needed to stave off bankruptcy before the IMF accord takes
effect.
   Failure to secure the emergency loans last week led Mikulic's
government to delay the lifting of a six-month wage and price
freeze imposed last November.
   Yugoslavs have been on a mass shopping spree in anticipation
that prices will jump sharply higher after lifting of the ban,
which only partially limited inflation.
   Living standards, which have already fallen by one-third since
1980, are expected to drop further, making strikes and social
unrest likely.
   The gap between the poor south and richer north of Yugoslavia is
also likely to increase, provoking more calls from wealthy Slovenia
and Croatia for a market-oriented economy with closer ties to
Western Europe.
</TEXT>
