<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AcidRain     05-15 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acid Rain,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air-Sea Effort Set to Measure Acid Rain</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT Sunday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government scientists will take to the sea and
air in July to measure the chemicals contributing to acid rain off
the mid-Atlantic coast.
   A research ship and aircraft will study chemicals in the air and
water between Norfolk, Va., and Bermuda, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration announced.
   Dr. Joe Boatman of the NOAA Air Resources Laboratory in Boulder,
Colo., said that the scientists will measure concentrations of
sulfur, nitrogen and other chemicals in an effort to track
pollution as it travels off the coast.
   Acidic rain, believed to result from the chemical reaction
between water in the air and chemical pollution from factories, has
been blamed for environmental damage in the Northeast and Canada,
among other areas.
   In addition, the Environmental Defense Fund recently charged
that this acid precipitation could be partly to blame for declines
in marine life in coastal areas including the Chesapeake and
Delaware bays and Long Island and Pamlico sounds.
   Boatman said the NOAA ship Mt. Mitchell and an agency aircraft
will make several trips between Bermuda and the East Coast to
measure the chemicals, determine their direction of travel and
predict how much reaches Bermuda and beyond.
</TEXT>
