<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Nazis     05-15 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Nazis,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 Right-Wing Extremists Detained After Giving Nazi Salute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 27 right-wing
extremists who held an illegal rally, gave the Nazi salute and
shouted Nazi slogans, officials said Sunday.
   The arrests occurred Saturday night at a square in Munich after
police briefly took into custody Michael Kuehnen, a 32-year-old
neo-Nazi leader.
   Kuehnen had been scheduled to speak at a meeting of the Bavarian
branch of the far-right Free Workers' Party in nearby Siegertsbrunn.
   Police said they feared Kuehnen could instigate violence if he
were allowed to speak at the meeting, which about 30 people
attended. He was released after the meeting was over.
   Right-wing extremists tried to hold a demonstration in front of
Munich's main police station to protest Kuehnen's detention but
were ordered to leave because they had no permit, police said.
   Twenty-seven of the protesters then went to a street corner and
began shouting Nazi slogans and giving the stiff-armed Nazi salute
before police arrived, officials said.
   Police said all but one of the demonstrators were released.
Police did not say whether that demonstrator, an 18-year-old
Austrian, would face charges.
   Estimates of the number of right-wing extremists in West Germany
range from 22,000 to more than 23,000.
</TEXT>
