<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Emergency     05-15 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Emergency,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopia Declares State Of Emergency In War-torn North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government declared a state of
emergency in the war-torn northern provinces of Eritrea and Tigre
and ordered border areas evacuated, government radio reported
Sunday.
   Western diplomats said the action raised fears that President
Mengistu Haile Mariam's communist government will use harsh tactics
to suppress Marxist separatists in the north, where the war has
made it difficult to get relief supplies to 3.2 million drought
victims.
   Addis Ababa Radio said the decree, issued Saturday, gave
security forces and administrators sweeping powers to fight the
Eritrean and Tigrean rebels in this East African nation.
   It said people and their property will be evacuated within 15
days from 6-mile-wide strips along Ethiopia's 1,500-mile border
with Sudan and along the 600-mile Red Sea coastline, excluding the
Eritrean port of Massawa.
   The report did not indicate how many people would be affected,
but the areas are sparsely populated.
   The decree, issued by the Council of State and signed by
Mengistu, establishes military and security councils to direct all
military and civilian activities and empowers them to transfer or
expel people and sequester private property for public service.
   Western diplomats said they were particularly concerned about a
section of the decree giving the councils power to declare any area
prohibited.
   ``It smacks of free-fire zones. ... Presumably the intention is
to say you get out of the area and if not, you're dead meat,'' said
one Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   President Reagan said last month that ``starvation and scorched
earth are being considered as weapons to defeat the rebellion.''
   Rebels of the secessionist Eritrean People's Liberation Front
have been fighting for 27 years in Africa's oldest civil war, and
guerrillas of the Tigre People's Liberation Front took up arms 14
years ago to demand more autonomy. They have won major victories
this year and captured several towns since February.
   Mengistu on March 31 said his government is starting a huge
counteroffensive. In his first acknowledgment of the war, Mengistu
said his troops were fighting a ``grim struggle'' against rebels in
the country's northernmost provinces.
   A week later, his government expelled from Eritrea and Tigre
about 60 foreign relief workers, citing ``personnel risks.''
   The action has crippled a massive Western relief operation.
Government officials have said indigenous organizations will
continue relief efforts, but insist that military objectives must
take priority over humanitarian needs.
   In Congress last month, Chester Crocker, U.S. assistant
secretary of state, accused Mengistu of banning relief workers to
hide the fighting.
   ``He doesn't want anyone to see what's going on up there,
because it's going to be bloody,'' Crocker told the Africa and
human rights subcommittees of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies in 1974 when, with a clique
of fellow army officers, he helped overthrow Emperor Haile Selassie.
</TEXT>
