<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-15 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Extremists Kill Five At Home Of Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists Sunday shot and
killed five people in a raid on the home of an official in
President Junius R. Jayewardene's governing United National Party.
   Military officers, who briefed reporters on condition of
anonymity, said the extremists attacked the home of B. Abeywickrene
in the town of Akuressa, 80 miles south of Colombo.
   Abeywickrene, secretary to the district's chief minister, was
not home at the time, the officers said.
   The victims were two police constables, a bodyguard assigned to
Abeywickrene and two civilians, the officers said.
   On Saturday, the extremists shot to death Serasinghe Nandapala,
a candidate from Jayewardene's party in upcoming local council
elections, police said.
   Both attacks were blamed on the People's Liberation Front, made
up of extremists from the ethnic Sinhalese majority opposed to
making concessions to the minority Tamils.
   The government announced Tuesday that it signed an accord with
the front to end its bloody attacks, which have taken the lives of
more than 260 politicians and government officials since last July.
But on Wednesday, the underground leader of the group denounced the
pact and said he had not signed it.
   The front has vowed to kill anyone who supports the
Indian-brokered peace accord signed last July 29 and aimed at
ending a five-year Tamil separatist war.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million population. They say they are discriminated against by
the Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the government and military.
   Sinhalese make up about 75 percent of the population. The rest
are Christian descendants of colonial settlers and Moslem
descendants of early Arab traders.
   India has sent more than 50,000 troops to the island to try to
enforce the accord. Most of the troops are in the north and east,
where the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam militia has continued
its insurgency despite the peace pact.
   India is involved because it is a regional power and because it
has 60 million ethnic Tamils in its southern states who are
sympathetic to their Sri Lankan brethren.
</TEXT>
