<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AndersonBook     05-15 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anderson Book,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Reagan Adviser Says Casey Maneuvered to Weaken Oversight of
CIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late CIA Director William J. Casey
successfully maneuvered to weaken White House oversight of U.S.
foreign intelligence operations while the Iran-Contra affair was
taking shape, according to a book by a former aide to President
Reagan.
   The book, ``Revolution,'' by Martin Anderson, published by
Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, also says that former White House chief
of staff Donald T. Regan abetted Casey in his move although he was
``uneasy'' about it.
   Anderson, who was Reagan's chief domestic policy adviser during
part of his first term and became a member of the President's
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board in his second term, describes
steps leading up to a reorganization of the board in November 1985.
   The board, originally 21 members, was reduced to 14 by firing 11
members and adding four new ones, making it what Anderson called a
``celebrity board.''
   ``When the 21-member-strong PFIAB that used to probe widely and
deeply without caution was transformed into a much smaller board,
dominated by famous, very busy people, one of the last effective
potential checks on Casey and the intelligence community was
gone,'' Anderson wrote.
   ``It is impossible to say for certain that if the old PFIAB was
in place the Iran-Contra affair would not have happened,'' he said.
``But a large, vigorous board would have made it more likely that
the skullduggery would have been discovered much, much earlier.''
   According to Anderson's account, the initial complaints about
the board's size came from Anne Armstrong, its chairman. He wrote
that Casey, however, ``did not like the old PFIAB'' and
``graciously allowed Mrs. Armstrong to be his stalking horse.''
   He wrote in the book that Robert C. McFarlane, then the
president's national security adviser, supported Casey and Mrs.
Armstrong, although he later told Anderson in an interview that he
regretted this.
   McFarlane had an aide, Kenneth de Graffenreid, draft a letter
reorganizing the board, which was sent to the president for his
consideration and signature, bypassing Regan.
   Reagan telephoned his chief of staff, according to an account
that Regan gave Anderson in an interview, and said, ``Don, why are
we firing all of these people?''
   Regan, caught by surprise, called Mrs. Armstrong, who told him
the board was so large it was unwieldy.
   Regan ``still felt uneasy,'' wrote Anderson. ``This was not
something he wanted responsibility for.''
   So he arranged a meeting for Mrs. Armstrong to make the case
directly to the president.
   Reagan approved the firings, which were announced on Nov. 4,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880515-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites Sub a0741 05-15 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, Sub, a0741,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To restore dropped first name of railroad chairman, subs 2nd
graf of OMAHA, Neb.-dated second item in rdp.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Union Pacific Railroad workers get to
rub elbows with the railroad's chairman in an unusual place _ in
the shower room of the company's new $500,000 fitness center.
   Chairman Michael Walsh said Friday that he showers and changes
clothes with the workers after he exercises at the new center at
the railroad's headquarters.
   ``I might be in the shower and some guy does a double-take,'' he
said.
   Curious employees will ask him, ``Aren't you the chairman?'' and
Walsh said he responds, ``Yes, nice to meet you.''
   The workers are surprised, Walsh said, because railroads have a
tradition of being ``very hierarchial organizations,'' in which top
managers and employees don't socialize.
   ``People are surprised when the chairman talks with them, let
alone shares a common shower,'' he said.
</TEXT>
