<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Paraguay Bjt   05-15 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Paraguay, Bjt,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papal Visit Magnifies Church-State Tensions in Paraguay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II's scheduled visit to
Paraguay has magnified a split between the 34-year-old
authoritarian government of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner and the
increasingly critical Roman Catholic clergy.
   The pontiff was scheduled to arrive Monday for a 57-hour visit
to this overwhelmingly Catholic country, the last stop on a 12-day
pilgrimage that has taken him to Uruguay, Bolivia and Peru.
   Perhaps the most politically sensitive stop, the visit has
spotlighted deteriorating ties between the church and the rightist
government, whose members often describe clerical critics as
communists and subversives.
   In turn, clerics _ 19 of whom have been expelled by the
government since 1969 _ frequently attack alleged government
corruption, election fraud and human and civil rights violations.
   Although the government and the church collaborated in drawing
up papal activities, each has accused the other of attempting to
manipulate the pope's visit for political purposes.
   A furor arose last week when the government abruptly canceled
``for security reasons'' a Tuesday night meeting of the pontiff and
the Builders of Society, a civic group that includes members of
opposition political parties not recognized by the government.
   Vatican pressure and two days of talks finally won a reversal.
The government agreed to allow the meeting in a state-run sports
arena but said it would hold the church responsible for ensuring
``its religious nature.''
   Jose Maria Troche of the Episcopal Conference said 3,800 people
had been invited to the meeting.
   But only 140 members of the government, President Stroessner's
ruling Colorado Party and the armed forces were included.
   Although the party, whose official newspaper Patria earlier
described the meeting as a ``corrupt assembly,'' made no official
comment, party spokesmen told Asuncion newspapers Sunday that
members would boycott the meeting.
   Party spokesmen said invitations were disproportionate with a
February national election that gave the party and Stroessner _
re-elected to eight straight terms after a 1954 coup _ 89 precent
of the vote. The opposition claims the election was fraudulent.
   Stroessner controls the government with his Colorado Party.
Though Paraguay has elections in which some recognized opposition
candidates are elected, two-thirds of Congress belong to the
Colorado Party.
   The church has criticized the decision to allow only
state-controlled radio and television to cover papal activities in
this nation of 3.8 million, where about 97 percent of the
population is Catholic.
   While Radio Caritas, the church station that often airs
interviews with opposition leaders, announced it would refrain from
government criticism during the papal visit, all stations _
including Caritas _ are obliged to relay official coverage.
   ``How can those who describe our bishops, priest and laymen as
communists hope to explain to our people the feelings of the
church?'' said Monsignor Pastor Cuquejo, auxiliary bishop of
Asuncion and coordinator of the Paraguay portion of the visit.
   Public reaction to the papal visit was mixed, although elaborate
preparations were nearing completion in this capital of 800,000 and
the four interior cities to be visited by the pontiff.
   ``Sure, there is a lot of enthusiasm, just look at that,'' said
a taxi driver as he pointed to a huge altar built near Asuncion's
international airport. Hundreds of army conscripts were cutting
grass with machetes around the city.
   Asuncion streets were freshly scrubbed and decorated with
welcoming banners.
   Yet there were signs of ennui. ``I think the people are plain
tired of the pope,'' said a Paraguayan journalist who requested
anonymity. ``Don't forget, this is his last stop, and people have
been following his trip since May 7.''
   He said his newspaper had received numerous calls from mothers
who complained that their children had lost too much class time in
practicing for papal events.
</TEXT>
