<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Guerrillas     05-15 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Guerrillas,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Commander Outlines Plans For Future Afghan Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: one name only for Mahmood and Najib</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla leader said Sunday
his fighters will attack the key Afghan city of Jalalabad as soon
as it is free of Red Army troops.
   Mahmood, a commander in the radical Hezb-I-Islami guerrilla
faction, made the claim as the first of an estimated 6,000 Soviet
soldiers left Jalalabad, a strategic city in northeastern
Afghanistan 45 miles west of the Pakistan border.
   The Soviet troops are reportedly being replaced by up to 12,000
soldiers from the Afghan army.
   ``There will be a lot of army there. It will need a lot of
pressure,'' Mahmood said.
   He said he had 10,000 men under his command near the city but
could not predict when Jalalabad, the heavily fortified capital of
Nangarhar province, would be in rebel hands.
   He explained that the city is surrounded by land mines, canals
and rivers.
   ``Some Mujahedeen cannot swim,'' Mahmood said with a sheepish
grin.
   Mujahedeen, or holy warrior, is a term the rebels use to
describe themselves. They have been fighting the Soviet-backed
communist government in Kabul for 10 years.
   Mahmood said his fighters would make full use of anti-aircraft
weapons to shoot down Soviet and Afghan helicopters as they
evacuate Soviet troops or resupply Kabul troops.
   The rebels claimed they shot down two Soviet MI-24 helicopter
gunships over Jalalabad on Friday.
   Accompanied by district commander Zurabgul Khomainy, Mahmood
said his fighters, in coordination with three other parties of
rebel fighters, would concentrate first on the security posts
surrounding Jalalabad, then work on clearing mines.
   The United States, a major arms supplier to the guerrillas, has
recently sent them sophisticated mine-clearing devices. As with
other commanders, Mahmood would not be specific about which weapons
his men possess but described their supply situation as ``less than
we wish.''
   Over the past month, the rebels reportedly have overrun dozens
of security posts in eastern Afghanistan as Soviet forces handed
them over to Kabul troops.
   ``The morale of the Mujahedeen is very good, but the morale of
the Kabul army is weak now,'' said Mahmood.
   The rebel forces recently proposed a limited amnesty to Afghan
regulars, saying that any troops who surrender within four weeks of
the Soviets' withdrawal will not be tried for war crimes.
   The fall of Jalalabad would be a major blow to Afghan President
Najib in his effort to keep his Marxist government in power after
the Soviet withdrawal.
   Under terms of an accord signed in Geneva in April, all Soviet
troops must be out of Afghanistan in nine months.
   Pakistan is a conduit of arms to the guerrillas and serves as
their headquarters. It also shelters about 3.5 million war refugees.
</TEXT>
