<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Suspected Kurdish Guerrillas Killed In Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERIK, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces Sunday surrounded a house
where seven suspected Kurdish insurgents were hiding and killed
them in a 1{-hour shootout, the Anatolia news agency reported.
   A Turkish soldier also was killed and two policemen were injured
after the trapped Kurds refused to surrender and fired on the
troops, the news agency said. The clash was in Bayrakli village in
southeastern Turkey near the Syrian border.
   Anatolia did not say what outlawed group the guerrillas belonged
to, but most of the insurgents operating in the region are linked
to the Kurdish Labor Party. The group seeks to set up a Marxist
state in parts of eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   After the clash, security forces seized five Soviet-made
Kalashnikov automatic rifles, one M-16 automatic rifle, seven hand
grenades, ammunition and illegal documents, the dispatch said.
   Last week, Kurdish rebels raided two hamlets and killed 25
villagers in Nusaybin, 50 miles east of Derik, and Sirnak, 110
miles east of Derik.
   Nearly 900 civilians and military personnel and about 900
Kurdish rebels have been killed since guerrillas started
hit-and-run attacks in 1984.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of
52 million.
