<1ST_LINE>r p AM-IowaDemocrats     05-15 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Democrats,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gains Ground as Iowa Democrats Pick Delegates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
continued to gain steam among Iowa Democrats, winning the bulk of
delegates selected at congressional district conventions this
weekend.
   Dukakis won 12 of the 34 delegates at stake, while backers of
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt were able to elect nine delegates
who are technically uncommitted.
   Gephardt won the state's Feb. 8 precinct caucuses, but has since
dropped out of the race. Many of the nine uncommitted delegates are
expected to endorse Dukakis.
   That group remained together to make it easier to elect their
leaders to cherished national delegate posts at the convention in
Atlanta, July 18-21. Party leaders list them as neutral, although
some insisted on carrying Gephardt's banner.
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' sole remaining active opponent, won
seven delegates, while Illinois Sen. Paul Simon collected six.
Simon has put his campaign on hold, but is still technically an
active candidate and eligible for delegates.
   Dukakis backers said they were satisfied with the outcome of the
six district conventions, and party officials said the results
showed Iowa joining the rest of the nation in handing the
Massachusetts governor the front-runner's mantle.
   ``I think certainly nobody should be surprised,'' said Iowa
Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder. ``Dukakis came out on top,
which is what he should have done.''
   He predicted Dukakis' margin would grow during the month leading
to the party's state convention on June 25, when 18 more delegates
will be selected. The state convention is the final step in Iowa's
four-step process of choosing delegates. The early round precinct
caucuses pushed Iowa into the national spotlight because it was the
nation's first contest, but no delegates were picked.
   In addition to the delegates elected at Saturday's conventions,
Iowa will send nine ``super delegates''_ party leaders and elected
officials whose titles won them seats as delegates _ to the
national convention.
   Two super delegates have already endorsed Dukakis, including
State Chairwoman Bonnie Campbell who came under criticism Saturday
at some of the conventions for her endorsement. Some activists
introduced resolutions calling for her to drop her support.
   ``If she had it to do all over again, she'd do the same thing,''
Roeder said, arguing that her endorsement was important in currying
favor with Dukakis in hopes of retaining the state's early place in
the nominating battle.
</TEXT>
