<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Mood     05-15 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Mood,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Withdrawal Is A Great Day But Peace Is Far Away</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghans and Pakistanis in this hot,
dusty border town agreed that Sunday was a great day because Soviet
troops were starting to leave Afghanistan, but they also agreed
that peace was still far away.
   ``Yes, I am happy. This is a great day, but only God knows when
there will be peace and I can go home,'' said Khaled, an Afghan
refugee from Kabul.
   He now runs a shop selling jewelry, Afghan carpets and war
souvenirs in Peshawar's squalid Saddar Bazaar.
   There were no celebrations in this city, headquarters of Moslem
anti-communist guerrillas, or in its sun-baked environs that are
temporary home to about 3.5 million refugees of the Afghan war.
   It was business as usual, although things were moving a bit
slowly as the local Moslems endured 104-degree heat, compounded by
the religious month, Ramadan, which forbids eating from sunrise to
sunset.
   Horse and bullock carts hauling sugar cane and fruits plodded
through the narrow smelly streets of the old city. Three-wheeled
taxis droned in and out of traffic, fouling the air with pungent
white exhaust.
   The only relief was a brief afternoon dust storm, which added
grime to sweaty brows.
   At the offices of the seven main guerrilla parties, the bearded
turbaned men alternately slept or continued to plan their
anti-communist war effort.
   Mahmood, a member of the Hezb-I-Islami faction and the chief
guerrilla commander of Afghanistan's eastern Nangarhar province,
said May 15 was no special day.
   ``For us, it's the same. We haven't just started fighting,'' he
said. ``We'll continue our holy war.''
   The idea, as so frequently explained by the guerrillas, is that
Afghanistan should be ruled by Moslems and not by the pro-Moscow
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, which they consider
atheist.
   In the money-changing market of the old city, business seemed
slow.
   ``People are fasting, they don't have the energy to trade,''
said Shabir, a Pakistani.
   Manshi, a Pakistani driver of a battered Toyota taxi, said he
was glad the Red Army was leaving Afghanistan because it would mean
the return of the refugees.
   ``They take our jobs because they work cheap,'' he said as he
swerved to avoid an oncoming truck, covered in chrome and painted
in a kaleidescope of colors.
   ``I know it's hard for them, but they cost us many many money.''
   For Peshawar, described by U.N. officials as the refugee capital
of the world, Sunday was the start of a new chapter in history.
   But the general feeling seemed to be that it wouldn't be printed
in ink until all Soviet troops leave Afghanistan and its Marxist
government falls.
</TEXT>
