<HEAD>Cuomo Rips Bush For Reagan Policies, Keeping Quiet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, saying Michael Dukakis
will likely take the Democratic presidential nomination, has been
blasting the apparent Republican nominee, George Bush.
   Cuomo, once seen as a possible Democratic nominee, attacked
Reagan administration policies at a Seattle fund-raiser on Satuday
night, and said the vice president must share the responsibility.
   ``I hope George Bush will...explain what happened in
Iran-Contra. I hope George Bush will ...tell us why he did business
with (Panamanian leader Manuel) Noriega, who has been pumping drugs
into our children,'' he said.
   ``We need a government we can believe when it speaks to its
people. We have been lied to by this government,'' said the New
York governor.
   Cuomo predicted a big Democratic victory in the fall.
   ``The story of November is going to be the shock, not that the
Democrats won, but by how much they won,'' he said.
   But he said his party has its work cut out for it. To start
with, he said, Democrats must assure supporters of Jesse Jackson
``that Jesse isn't the only one who is concerned about the drug
problem, concerned about education, concerned about corporations
that leave this country to manufacture in foreign lands using cheap
labor.''
   Cuomo's appearance in Seattle was the end of a two-day West
Coast tour that started with an appearance for Rep. Nancy Pelosi in
San Francisco Friday night and a foreign policy speech before the
World Affairs Council of Oregon in Portland earlier Saturday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jackson Leader Says Nothing Gained From State Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's Georgia campaign chairman,
state Sen. Eugene Walker, has called off his challenge to incumbent
Democratic National Committee member Herb Mabry.
   A threatened challenge to Gov. Joe Frank Harris for leadership
of the state delegation to the Democratic National Convention did
not materialize.
   Decatur Mayor Michael Mears, the co-chairman of the state
Jackson campaign, said no progress was made on a list of
initiatives supported by the campaign.
   He said Harris refused to meet with him to talk about the
initiatives, which include helping blacks win local offices and
Supreme Court seats, giving Jackson backers paid party jobs,
putting more blacks and women in state management jobs, allowing
voter registration by mail and eliminating the Confederate battle
flag from the state flag.
   ``It's Old Guard 1, Jackson nothing,'' said Mears.
   Walker opened the meeting on Saturday by withdrawing his
candidacy for the Democratic National Committee member Herb Mabry,
the state AFL-CIO president. Mabry has held the seat for 15 years.
   Andrew Griffin Jr., a black supporter of Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis said the standing ovation Walker received when he
withdrew from the national committee race might be a sign that
party leaders appreciate the Jackson campaign's efforts for unity.
   ``You could feel the sigh of relief,'' Griffin said. ``Now, the
party executives might say, `We owe them one _ they put unity above
everything else.'''
