<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-15 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Celebrate Capture of Jerusalem; Arabs Mark `Day of
Calamity'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI C. RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Israelis attended ceremonies
Sunday marking the 21st anniversary of the capture of Jerusalem's
Arab sector. Arab stores observed a strike on what Palestinian
protesters called a ``day of calamity.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir vowed Jerusalem would remain
Israel's capital forever and said his government would never give
up the West Bank and Gaza Strip, occupied by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Stores were shut throughout the occupied lands and in Arab East
Jerusalem in response to an order by leaders of the 5-month-old
Palestinian uprising to mark a ``day of calamity.'' Only scattered
protests were reported.
   The army clamped a curfew on the Shati refugee camp in Gaza and
the village of Anabta in the West Bank after disturbances the night
before.
   A 60-year-old Palestinian from Hebron died of a head wound
suffered in a beating four days ago, an official at the Moslem
Mukassad Hospital said Sunday.
   Palestinians accused Jewish settlers of beating Ibrahim Abu
Aishe, but an army spokesman quoted Aishe's family as saying
Palestinians attacked the man for violating an earlier strike
called by the underground leadership of the uprising.
   The latest death raised to 188 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8. A soldier and an Israeli teen-ager
also have died.
   Israel radio quoted an Israeli legislator, Yair Tzaban of the
left-wing Mapam party, as saying high school students recently beat
jailed Palestinians under the guidance of their paramilitary youth
group commander. The army had no comment on the report.
   Shamir spoke at a ceremony on Ammunition Hill, site of one of
the fiercest battles in which Israel's army seized East Jerusalem
from Jordan in 1967.
   ``There are still those who shun Jerusalem,'' Shamir told a
crowd of about 1,000. ``To all these we will say: Take your hands
off Jerusalem. No force in the world will change her destiny ... as
Israel's eternal capital and fortress of strength.''
   Although Jerusalem is Israel's declared capital and the seat of
the national government, few countries recognize it as such.
   Throughout the festivities marking the Hebrew calendar
anniversary of what Israelis call the city's reunification, there
were reminders of the Palestinian uprising.
   At the Wailing Wall, the only remaining outer wall of the
biblical Jewish Temple and Judaism's holiest site, youngsters and
organized tour groups passed through rigorous security checks to
enter the courtyard compound.
   Police barred a group of Jewish extremists, followers of
American Rabbi Meir Kahane, from visiting the Temple Mount to pray
Sunday morning, Israel radio reported.
   The hill is known in Arabic as Haram al-Sharif and contains the
Dome of the Rock, where Moslems believe Mohammed ascended to heaven.
   Jews also consider the Temple Mount holy as the site of two
ancient Jewish temples, one built by the biblical King Solomon.
   In other developments Sunday:
   _A military court sentenced Sgt. Maj. Charlie Danino to four
months in jail and demoted him to private for allowing soldiers
under his command to bury alive four Palestinians on the West Bank
last February. The Palestinians were later rescued.
   _Israeli authorities restored press credentials to Glenn Frankel
of the Washington Post, whose press card was taken away when he
wrote that Israeli commandoes carried out the assassination of
Palestine Liberation Organization official Khalil Wazir last month
in Tunis.
   _World Jewish Congress president Edgar Bronfman told a news
conference after a trip to Moscow that the Soviet Union had
softened its terms for an international peace conference on the
Middle East.
   Bronfman said the Soviets now agreed the conference should not
have authority to dictate a solution to the parties concerned.
</TEXT>
