<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 05-15 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0782,0886</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Pullout Begins With Retreat From Jalalabad</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with color from Soviet arrival
in Kabul. PICKS up 6th graf pvs,, `The convoy ...' EDITS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos KAB1,KAB2,KAB3,KAB4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red Army troops lumbered into Kabul on
Sunday after a daylong journey through mountains teeming with
guerrillas as the Soviet Union began its retreat from more than
eight years of war in Afghanistan.
   The 300-vehicle convoy set out at 7:30 a.m. for the 88-mile trip
from Jalalabad, passing through crowds of Afghan children who threw
flowers and an occasional clod of dirt or dung.
   As the motorized rifle unit crossed the towering mountains
separating Jalalabad from Kabul, shots rang out from distant hills
and the procession backed up in spots along the rough, one-way road.
   No casualties were reported.
   At 3:30 p.m., the convoy reached Kabul. About 2,000 Afghans
lined four miles of highway leading into the city, said a Western
photographer.
   Many of them were soldiers or members of communist youth
organizations, dressed in red shirts with white scarves.
   ``Today the Soviets are leaving. I'm happy for them,'' said Abdu
Samir, a 20-year-old soldier, as he watched the procession move
into Kabul.
   Samir said he hoped the Afghan army would be strong enough to
withstand attacks from anti-communist guerrillas.
   ``Long Live Friendship Between Afghanistan And The Soviet
Union,'' read a white banner, flapping along the highway. Stenciled
posters of a waving Soviet soldier were tacked up nearby.
   The Soviets planned to spend the night in Kabul before starting
the 200-mile trip to the Soviet border Monday.
   The convoy out of Jalalabad was the first of four that will
leave the northeastern city near the Pakistan border. As it made
its way toward Kabul, a guerrilla leader vowed that his men would
attack Jalalabad.
   Mahmood, a commander in the Hezb-I-Islami guerrilla faction,
said his 10,000 men would invade the city as soon as the Red Army
was out.
   Lt. Gen. Vladimir Bogdanov said the convoys would leave on
alternate days to allow traffic in the opposite direction to use
the road but that all Soviets based in Jalalabad would be withdrawn
within two weeks.
   Anti-Communist rebels fighting the Soviet-backed government of
President Najib control some of the mountainous regions through
which the convoy passed.
   Twenty Western journalists were brought to Jalalabad to ride
with the convoy to Kabul, and during the night spent in the
garrison city they heard heavy bombardment and felt the impact of a
surface-to-surface missile that landed 90 feet from their hotel.
   Information about the start of the withdrawal was provided by a
Reuters news agency pool report. Associated Press reporters were
barred from covering the event. Soviet officials said the exclusion
was the result of questions asked by the AP during a previous trip
to Kabul.
   Edmund McWilliams, deputy chief-of-mission at the U.S. Embassy
in Kabul, said the rebels have moved in closer to the capital and
stepped up attacks.
   ``We've had, as you may know, this past week, quite a bit of
rocketing of the city, and we're expecting possibly some more
rocketing tonight,'' McWilliams said Sunday. ``It does not appear,
though, at this point that the attacks ... will be affecting the
pullout.''
   Soviet troops and tanks moved into Afghanistan on Dec. 27, 1979
to fight the anti-communist insurgency and replace one pro-Soviet
government with another.
   About 115,000 Soviet troops are in Afghanistan to bolster
Najib's forces, but all must pull back to Soviet territory within
the next nine months to comply with U.N.-mediated peace accords
signed in Geneva last month.
   Half the troops must leave by Aug. 15 under the agreement. Lt.
Gen. Boris Gromov told reporters Saturday that about one quarter of
the soldiers would be home before President Reagan visits Moscow on
May 29.
   The Soviet's departure will leave Najib's army of 50,000 alone
in its battle against about 200,000 Moslem insurgents. The
guerrillas have vowed to fight on to topple the Marxist government.
   Guerrillas and Western observers estimate that about 1.5 million
Afghans have died in the war.
   The U.S. State Department estimates Soviet casualties since 1979
at 33,000-38,000, more than one-third of whom were killed.
   On Sunday, the Communist Party leadership in Moscow addressed
the departing troops with words of thanks and a call for their help
in improving Soviet life once they return home.
   ``Days of severe trials lie behind you,'' said the party Central
Committee address, printed on the front page of the party daily
Pravda. ``You have fulfilled the order of your homeland.''
   Tass reported that Najib sent a message of thanks to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Sunday, praising the ``heroic feat''
of the Soviets in helping defend his government.
   In a joint Soviet-Afghan statement carried by the official
Soviet news agency, the allied governments said the ``pivotal
issue'' in ending the civil war that has gripped Afghanistan for a
decade would be ensuring an end to ``interference from the outside
in the home affairs of the Afghans.''
   Soviet and Afghan officials have accused the United States and
Pakistan of exacerbating the war by delivering arms to the rebels.
</TEXT>
