<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     05-15 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Walesa,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Addresses Tens of Thousands at Mass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told tens of
thousands of worshipers at an outdoor Mass on Sunday that Poles
will ``give their all'' for the country only when their rights are
ensured.
   It was the biggest public appearance by Walesa since he and
about 1,000 followers emerged from the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk on
Tuesday to end a 9-day sit-in.
   The strikers gave up without winning concessions on pay or
recognition of Solidarity, the trade union federation outlawed
after the imposition of martial law in 1981.
   The Mass was celebrated in Walesa's home city of Gdansk, where
Pope John Paul II praised Solidarity during a visit to Poland 11
months ago.
   ``Workers and students keep Solidarity young and understand that
only solidarity of people and social groups can be the key to
overcoming the crisis in our homeland,'' said Walesa, who spoke for
about 10 minutes at the end of the Mass.
   ``People are willing to give their all for the common good only
when their full rights are safeguarded,'' he said.
   Aides to Walesa estimated the crowd at 50,000, while Western
journalists said there were at least 30,000 people.
   The Mass was celebrated by Wroclaw Bishop Cardinal Henryk
Gulbinowicz, who has special responsibility for workers within the
Polish church. It was attended by 30 bishops.
   The service culminated a series of devotions nationwide in honor
of the Black Madonna, the medieval painting that is Poland's most
revered icon.
   ``We thank you, mother of God, for the strength to survive the
past eight years,'' Walesa said, referring to the martial law
period of 1981-83 and Poland's current economic crisis. He said
Poles still have the courage to say: ``There is no freedom without
Solidarity.''
   Walesa was the final speaker among several people representing
various social groups.
   The gathering was predominantly religious, with almost no
Solidarity banners in evidence. Afterwards, people dispersed
peacefully.
   Walesa aide Bogdan Olszewski said in a telephone interview that
there has been no police harassment of people who took part in the
shipyard strike, which occurred during two weeks of labor unrest _
Poland's worst since strikes swept the nation in 1980.
   The official PAP news service reported absenteeism only slightly
higher than normal at the 10,800-worker shipyard Thursday.
   All but six of 38 people arrested when police broke up a strike
at the Lenin steelworks in Nowa Huta in southern Poland on May 5
have been ordered freed, said Jan Rokita, a Krakow-area Solidarity
activist.
   The six still under arrest were strike committee members, said
Rokita. He said they are accused of leading an illegal strike,
punishable by up to three years in prison.
</TEXT>
