<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StealthCosts     05-15 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth Costs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stealth Bomber Now Estimated to Cost $450 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force's planned Stealth bomber has
risen in cost to an estimated $450 million per plane, making it the
most expensive aircraft ever built, The Washington Post reported in
its Sunday editions.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified U.S. officials, said the Air
Force has told a few members of Congress that its fleet of 132
Stealth bombers will cost at least 20 percent more than projected.
The Northrop Corp. is building the planes.
   At the same time, the Stealth fighter, which is flying, has been
kept in production under a secret deal worked out by Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, the Post
said.
   A Defense Department spokesman, Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, had no
comment on the report.
   The bomber fleet's advertised price tag, in fiscal 1981 dollars,
has jumped from $36.6 billion to $43 billion. When expressed in
1989 dollars, which accounts for inflation since 1981, the cost has
risen from $50.6 billion to $59.5 billion.
   The Stealth bomber is designed with a curvy shape and an
absorbent skin, which should enable it to evade Soviet radar for a
longer period than conventional aircraft, giving defenders less
time to react and knock the invader down.
   The bomber's estimated $450 million price tag, which some
analysts expect to go higher in the future, compares with the
estimated $278 million for the B-1B bomber and $136 million for the
C-5B giant transport.
   The Stealth fighters now in operation have some of the same
characteristics as the Stealth bomber but cannot fly as far or
carry as many weapons. The Lockheed Corp., which builds the Stealth
fighter, has been lobbying Congress to build a second group of the
planes to help fill the arms gap to be left in Europe when
medium-range nuclear weapons are eliminated under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces (INF) treaty, according to
congressional officials who spoke to the newspaper.
   Nunn, in negotiations on the fiscal 1988 military procurement
bill late last year, persuaded his colleagues to authorize extra
millions to buy additional Lockheed Stealth fighters to replace
some that crashed, the paper said. But the money added to the
secret so-called ``black budget'' was for less than six of the
Stealth fighters and not for the new group of planes Lockheed
sought, the officials told the Post.

</TEXT>
