<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FenceDeath     05-15 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fence Death,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbor Faces Manslaughter Charge in Death of Woman on His
Electric Fence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old merchant marine retiree has
been charged with manslaughter in the death of a longtime neighbor
who died when she tried to free one of her pet dogs from the man's
electrified fence.
   He had put up the fence to ward off a marauding pack of dogs,
but it was not installed properly and contained a lethal strength
of electric current, police said.
   The victim, 73-year-old Bertha Augusta Brittingham, was buried
Friday. Although a neighbor managed to free her from the fence, Ms.
Brittingham was dead on arrival Tuesday at a hospital in Cambridge.
   James Joseph Kahl, who for many years had lived next door to Ms.
Brittingham in a rural Dorchester County area, is free on his own
recognizance pending a court hearing on a date to be set.
   He declined Friday to discuss the death, other than to say it
was a difficult experience and that he has removed the electric
fence.
   Police said that when Kahl put up the 20-foot-long electric
fence, he failed to install a regulator that would have sent
pulsating current through the wire, instead of a steady flow of 110
volts that killed the elderly woman.
   ``That amount of voltage could kill anyone. It's like grabbing a
metal lamp with a frayed wire and not being able to let go of it,''
said Roger L. Layton of the Maryland State Police.
</TEXT>
