<2ND_LINE>AM-People-RFK's Children,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bobby Kennedy's Children Stress Involvement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed for release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the children of Robert F. Kennedy growing
older means becoming more involved in the government, in their
communities and in remembering their father.
   ``By taking us to Senate hearings, to political rallies, to the
playgrounds he built for ghetto children, he taught each of us that
participation in public affairs was worthy and honorable,''
36-year-old Kathleen Kennedy Townsend says of her father in the
June issue of Life magazine.
   Mrs. Townsend, who lost a 1986 congressional bid, is the
director of a Maryland program for teen-agers.
   Rep. Joseph Kennedy II, 35, who holds the Massachusetts
congressional seat once held by his uncle, President John F.
Kennedy, has sponsored legislation for the homeless and for
increased involvement by banks in community programs.
   ``The rich,'' he says, ``can take care of themselves, but the
ordinary, hard working Americans can't afford the basic necessities
of living in the U.S. today.''
   Robert Kennedy Jr., 34, teaches environmental law at New York's
Pace University and is a lawyer for enviromental-protection groups.
   Courtney Kennedy Ruhe, 31, serves as treasurer of brother
Joseph's 1988 re-election campaign and is a member of the JFK
Library board. She also heads fund-raising for the RFK Memorial.
   Michael Kennedy, 30, is president of the Citizens Energy Corp.,
a Boston company founded by Joseph to supply inexpensive fuel and
prescription drugs to low-income families.
   Kerry Kennedy, 28, serves as executive director of the RFK
Memorial Center for Human Rights, which supports the work of
political activists around the world.
   Christopher Kennedy, 24, is a leasing agent at a family-owned
trade center in Chicago and devotes time to raising money for a
food bank.
   Douglas Kennedy, 21, a college student, is a member of the
Community for Creative Non-Violence and works with the homeless.
His 23-year-old brother, Maxwell, is also a college student.
   RFK's youngest child, 19-year-old Rory, is a college student who
has been arrested for protesting against South Africa.
   ``I guess my interest stemmed from numerous discussions at the
dinner table about South Africa and its relevance to what my father
believed and protested against when he went there in 1966,'' she
said.

</TEXT>
