<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance-Wash     05-15 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance-Wash,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Friendly U.S-Canada Border Is Not So Friendly These Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drugs-Zero Tolerance, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some are angry, others are sorry. But all of the
people caught up in the ``zero tolerance'' crackdown at the
U.S.-Canada border walk away without their car or truck.
   Many also have had to pay on-the-spot fines ranging up to $1,000
as their cost of the new attitude of the U.S. Customs Service
toward drugs _ even small amounts _ at the border crossing.
   Since March 21, 103 people have been arrested, 244 vehicles
seized and one boat taken because any amount of drugs were found,
Dan Holland, district U.S. Customs Service director for Washington
state, said last week.
   Every Thursday the victims of the crackdown can be found at U.S.
District Court hoping to reclaim their vehicles.
   One Canadian citizen complained that customs inspectors laughed
as they seized his $45,000 1988 Porsche at Blaine, Wash. Inside the
car was a gram of marijuana, enough to fit in the palm of a hand.
   Another said customs inspectors used tweezers to remove the .1
of a gram of marijuana _ enough to fit on the end of a finger _
discovered at the bottom of her purse.
   A third held for six hours after his arrest said: ``The only
people they stopped and inspected were people wearing jeans and
jean jackets. No one wearing a suit was stopped.''
   All three commented after the court session Thursday only on
condition that they not be named.
   ``It's down to almost the ridiculous,'' said Michael Martin, a
federal public defender representing some ``zero tolerance''
victims in the Northwest.
   ``I spent all day doing `zero tolerance' cases. I have serious
felony cases pending, and this takes away from my ability to handle
those cases. The impact in time is enormous, but the impact on
these individuals (defendants) is horrendous.''
   Lawrence LaDage, chief customs agent in Seattle, says there's no
room for flexibility.
   ``We're hoping the word will get out: Leave your dope at home or
knock it off,'' said LaDage.
   ``There is a lot of remorse, a lot of amazement _ the
realization that maybe this is serious after all,'' LaDage said.
``Mostly, it is utter disbelief. You have a brand new Trans Am ...
and all of a sudden you are walking.''
   Approximately 60 cases have gone through the federal court in
Seattle. Each involved a misdemeanor count of possession of a
controlled substance _ mostly marijuana _ and one felony count of
importing a controlled substance.
   In each case, the defendant pleaded guilty to the misdemeanor
count and was placed on a year's probation; the felony count was
dismissed, said Peter Voelker, criminal supervisor at the court.
   In a minority of cases to date, customs has assessed owners of
vehicles sizable fees to recover their impounded vehicles. The rest
will be sold at auction, LaDage said.
   Federal public defender Thomas Hillier said court-appointed
attorneys are recommending their clients go along with the guilty
pleas.
   ``The government has a hammer in the sense that nobody in their
right mind wants to go through the hardship of a criminal trial,''
Hillier said. ``You risk a felony conviction on the notion of
fighting for the general principle of the thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
