<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Media     05-15 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Media,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Returns Press Credentials To American Reporter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Sunday returned the press
credentials of a Washington Post reporter after suspending them
last month when he reported Israel carried out the assassination of
a top PLO official.
   Government officials said Glenn Frankel, the Post's Jerusalem
bureau chief, had violated military regulations by not submitting
his dispatch to army censors.
   Yoram Ettinger, head of the press office, said the government
returned the press card after receiving a letter from Frankel
saying he was aware of military regulations.
   Frankel's credentials were suspended April 26 along with those
of Martin Fletcher of NBC, who also reported an Israeli role in the
assassination of Khalil Wazir, military comander of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad, was slain April 16 at his home
in Tunis, the Tunisian capital, by a group of commandos. Israeli
sources have confirmed Israel carried out the attack but the
government has refusd comment.
   Ettinger said the government would keep Fletcher's credentials
until completing an investigation of another NBC story on a planned
army incursion into southern Lebanon on May 2 hours before the
operation began.
   ``We decided that until the issue of the Lebanon story is
resolved, we cannot return Fletcher's card,'' Ettinger said.
   Frankel said he was pleased his card was returned but that he
and his paper did not regret their actions.
   ``We stand by what we did. It was an important story,'' he said.
``We think the government's action was a mistake and we are glad
they rectified it.''
   Under Israeli law, journalists must submit reports relating to
security matters to military censors. The government has not
clearly defined security, however, leaving the submission of
reports to the journalists' discretion.
</TEXT>
