<HEAD>Rain, Thunderstorms Cover Parts of Plains, Great Lakes and
Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms stretched from the central Plains to
the western Great Lakes and also covered much of the southern
Appalachians Sunday, while sunny skies predominated over the rest
of the nation.
   Temperatures rose again into the upper 80s and low 90s in the
southern and central Mississippi Valley, and the warm air reached
into the lower Ohio Valley.
   In southwestern Michigan, thunderstorms dumped 1} inch hail on
Benton Harbor and pelted Tekonsha, Mich., and Joliet, Ill., with
three-quarter inch hail.
   Thunderstorms stretched from southeast Kansas and central
Missouri to Illinois, Wisconsin and Michigan.
   Wichita, Kan., recorded just over half an inch of rain in the
six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT. Rainfall elsewhere totalled less
than a quarter of an inch in the period.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also extended from northern
Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia to western Virginia and West
Virginia.
   Rain also was scattered over the coast of the Carolinas and
northeast Minnesota.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 43 degrees at Grand
Forks, N.D., to 98 degrees at Glendale, Ariz., and Needles, Calif.
The nation's low Sunday morning was 25 degrees at Lake Yellowstone,
Wyo., and Houlton, Maine.
   Rain and thunderstorms were forecast to stretch Monday from New
England and the Great Lakes to the Appalachians, Kentucky and the
Tennessee Valley, and showers were expected in the Pacific
Northwest. Skies were forecast to be generally sunny over the rest
of the nation.
   Highs were predicted to be in the upper 50s and the 60s over
much of New England and across the upper Great Lakes; in the 60s in
the Pacific Northwest and along the California coast; in the upper
80s to near 90 over the Gulf States; and in the 90s to near 110
degrees from inland portions of southern California through the
Southwest deserts. Highs were forecast in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
