<HEAD>Robert Redford Presents His ``Miracle'' Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Redford presented the latest film
he directed, ``The Milagro Beanfield War,'' at the Cannes Film
Festival Sunday after showing a selection of his films in three
Soviet cities.
   Speaking at a news conference, Redford said he had been told the
response to ``Milagro'' had been very strong in Soviet Georgia.
   ``Maybe its because they feel isolated from the rest of the
country there,'' he said.
   The film is not entered in the competition at the Cannes
festival, but Redford said he came to Cannes ``because the film is
very important for me and I was in the neighborhood.''
   ``The Milagro Beanfield War'' is about the inhabitants of
Milagro, a small town in New Mexico, and a resident who diverts
water from a real estate development to irrigate a patch of his
land.
   Redford, known for his interest in environmental issues, said
the cultural aspect of the story attracted him.
   ``The rampant development that's going on in the U.S. should be
questioned,'' he said. ``But there is also the need to preserve a
400-year-old culture.''
   He said he was aware of the Hispanic tradition in the United
States having grown up in a Mexican community in Los Angeles.
