<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims New Tanker Attack, Iran Says U.S. Helped Iraq</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs ``The raid...'' with further
identification of Seawise Giant. Pickup 13th graf pvs ``The
other...''; SUBS 25th graf ``He said...'' with one graf to ADD
hometowns of Navy helicopter crewmen. Pickup 26th graf pvs ``Tehran
said...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq claimed its warplanes hit another
supertanker off Iran's coast Sunday, and Tehran accused the U.S.
Navy of jamming radar and radio to aid Iraqi jets in a devastating
raid on a key oil terminal.
   Also Sunday, a Pentagon spokesman in Washington said the
wreckage of a U.S. helicopter that disappeared after heavy
U.S.-Iranian fighting last month was recovered along with the
bodies of its two crewmen.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman
as saying that Iraqi fighter-bombers attacked a ``large naval
target,'' its term for an Iranian tanker, during the night.
   There was no independent confirmation of that raid, the 11th
claimed by Baghdad in 17 days.
   The Iranians vowed revenge on the United States for Saturday's
Iraqi raid on the Larak oil facility in the Strait of Hormuz. Five
tankers, including two of the world's largest, were left in flames.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, quoted Prime Minister Hussein Musavi as branding the
Americans ``international hoodlums.''
   Speaking after a Cabinet meeting in Tehran, Musavi said
President Reagan is ``gradually pushing the U.S. to a war which
will make the Persian Gulf an American graveyard,'' IRNA reported.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said the
bodies of 17 seamen were recovered and that three other crewmen
were missing from Saturday's raid. Earlier, it had said up to 50
crewmen might have been lost.
   Four of the ships were badly damaged in the long-range air
strike on the terminal in the southern Persian Gulf.
   In Madrid, shipping officials and newspapers said the
Spanish-flagged 235,000-ton supertanker Barcelona had sunk.
   But a Spanish Foreign Ministry spokesman, Lloyd's, and
gulf-based shipping executives all said the supertanker, severely
damaged by fire, had been run aground to keep it from sinking.
   The raid came as the Barcelona took on oil from the 564,739-ton
Seawise Giant, the world's largest vessel. The Seawise Giant, a
Liberian-registered tanker chartered by Iran as a floating storage
depot, was reported severely damaged.
   The other ships hit in the raid were the 152,004-ton
Cypriot-flag Argosy, the 231,712-ton Iranian tanker Khark, and the
457,841-ton British-flag Burmah Endeavor.
   The Iraqi air strikes are part of Baghdad's campaign to cripple
Iran's vital oil industry and force Tehran to negotiate an end to
the 7{-year-old gulf war.
   Larak serves international customers picking up oil brought down
the gulf by Iran's own shuttle fleet.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Cyprus, on Sunday quoted a senior
Iranian air force officer who said that, as the Iraqi planes
approached their targets, ``the U.S. fleet began carrying out
electronic warfare against our planes,'' jamming Iranian systems
for nine minutes.
   U.S. military officials were not available for comment on the
claim. But two U.S. officials said Saturday that none of the U.S.
warships patrolling the gulf were involved in any way with the
Larak raid.
   IRNA reported that the Swiss Charge d'Affaires in Tehran, who
handles American interests, was summoned to the Foreign Ministry
and handed ``a strongly worded protest note.''
   Gulf-based shipping officials said they had reports that the
Iraqi planes that raided Larak went in at low altitude to drop
parachute bombs, rather than using missiles, which have proved
relatively ineffective in many attacks on the huge vessels.
   Fires aboard the tankers were reported under control Sunday,
except on the Barcelona, where flames were still breaking out while
salvage tugs worked to put them out.
   In Madrid, Spain's Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordolez
called in Iraq's ambassador and ``energetically condemned'' the
attack on the Barcelona.
   Meanwhile, in the southern gulf, two salvage tugs and a large
floating crane were lifting what maritime sources said was the
wreckage of a U.S. helicopter gunship that vanished April 18, the
day the U.S. Navy clashed with Iranian warships.
   Maritime executives said the wreckage was found during the
weekend by a salvage tug in the area of the clashes.
   In Washington, Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman,
confirmed the wreckage was located Sunday.
   He said the bodies of the two pilots _ Capt. Kenneth Hill, 33,
of Thomasville, N.C., and Capt. Stephen Leslie, 30, of New Bern,
N.C. _ had been recovered. They were the only American casualties
in the April fighting.
   Tehran said 44 Iranians were killed.
   The Marine Corps AH-1 Cobra disappeared hours after the fighting
in which the Americans destroyed two Iranian oil platforms and sank
or disabled six naval craft.
</TEXT>
