<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderforHire     05-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder for Hire,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Racehorse' Haynes Returns to Amarillo in Murder-for-Hire Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flamboyant attorney Richard ``Racehorse''
Haynes is back at the scene of one of his greatest legal triumphs.
   Eleven years after pulling off a stunning acquittal here for
former Fort Worth millionaire T. Cullen Davis, accused of killing
his stepdaughter and his wife's boyfriend, Haynes has returned to
defend Jane Ada Callaway, accused of masterminding the murder of
her boss' wife.
   Opening arguments were scheduled to begin Monday in a
large-capacity Potter County courtroom repainted for the trial with
money donated by Amarillo defense lawyers. Jury selection in the
capital murder case consumed more than a month.
   The Houston secretary's trial was moved here on a change of
venue from Houston, the same circumstances that in 1977 brought
Haynes to Amarillo from Fort Worth to defend Davis.
   To keep the lid on extensive publicity about the trial, Houston
State District Judge Michael McSpadden has issued a gag order
prohibiting attorneys and witnesses from discussing the trial.
   Haynes' challenge this time is to puncture a strong state case
against Ms. Callaway, charged with hiring a gunman to kill Judy
Saragusa on Sept. 2, 1987.
   Mrs. Saragusa's husband, Michael, was Ms. Callaway's boss and
the co-owner of a wholesale liquor distributorship. During pretrial
hearings, Saragusa admitted he had had an affair with Ms. Callaway,
but said it had ended two months before his 39-year-old wife's
slaying in the bedroom of the couple's mansion.
   The twice-divorced, 36-year-old Ms. Callaway is free on $50,000
bail and had to be ordered by a judge to stop telephoning her
former boss.
   After police identified a car seen leaving the murder scene as
belonging to Ms. Callaway, she signed a police statement saying she
had lent her car on the night of the shooting to Michael
Richardson, accused of being the middleman in the murder plot.
   Richardson's stepbrother, Leon Hawkins Jr., surrendered to
police two days after the shooting and told reporters, ``They made
me do it'' after being charged with capital murder.
   Richardson has agreed to testify for the state in exchange for a
10-year prison sentence, his attorney John Ackerman said last week.
   ``It's not an open and shut case, but it's a very good case,''
prosecutor Chuck Rosenthal told the Houston Post shortly after the
murder about the evidence against Ms. Callaway.
   Saragusa, expected to be another of the state's key witnesses,
is likely to be subjected to Haynes' famous cross-examination.
   Haynes' ruthless questioning of Priscilla Davis, Davis'
estranged wife, essentially put her on trial for her extramarital
affairs and drug use.
   Davis was acquitted of going on a 1976 shooting spree that left
Priscilla's daughter and boyfriend dead in Davis' $6 million
mansion, despite the testimony of three eyewitnesses identifying
Davis as the black-wigged gunman.
</TEXT>
