<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Waldheim     05-15 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Waldheim,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bronfman: Western And Soviet Secret Services Knew of Waldheim's
War Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Western intelligence agencies knew
of Kurt Waldheim's World War II past but did not block his
selection as U.N. secretary-general in hopes of using him for
political gains, a U.S. Jewish leader said Sunday.
   Edgar Bronfman, president of the New York-based World Jewish
Congress, also said his organization gave the Soviets a list of
50,000 names of Nazi war criminals that were obtained from U.S.
files.
   Bronfman made his comments at a news conference after flying to
Jerusalem from Moscow, where he said he met with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   ``It has become inreasingly clear that every secret service,
including the Americans, knew of Waldheim's war record,'' Bronfman
said.
   Waldheim, president of Austria since his election in June 1986,
served as U.N. secretary-general from 1972-1982. He has denied
allegations that he was involved in war crimes while serving as a
lieutenant in the German army in the Balkans during World War II.
   ``Everybody felt that they had something on Waldheim so he would
behave,'' Bronfman said. ``So it was agreed to let Waldheim become
secretary general of the United Nations.''
   Bronfman declined to say how he knew Western and Soviet
intelligence knew of Waldheim's war past and did not explain how
Walheim may have been pressured while U.N. secretary-general.
   An Austrian-appointed international panel of six historians
concluded in February that Waldheim knew about Nazi wartime
atrocities while serving in the Balkans in 1942-45. But the
committee found no evidence that Waldheim committed war crimes.
   In 1947, the Yugoslav government included Waldheim's name on a
list of suspected war criminals, but soon dropped a request to
Austria for his extradition without explanation.
   A British newspaper, the Sunday Express, asserted last year the
Yugoslav information left Waldheim open to Soviet bloc blackmail.
   The paper said it had a Dec. 12, 1947, memo from Uros N.
Djaelic, then chief of Yugoslavia's legal bureau, that detailed
what it called Waldheim's involvement in war crimes.
   The Sunday Exparess quoted the memo as saying: ``Waldheim, who
was responsible for hostages and contacts with collaborators ...
can be of value to the interests of Yugoslavia.''
   It quoted Anon Kolendic, the senior intelligence officer for
Yugoslavia in 1948, as saying he gave information on Waldheim to
the Soviet secret service.
   The paper reported a spokesman for Waldheim denied the
allegations.
   Another World Jewish Congress official, Ilan Steinberg, said
private investigators are now looking into Waldheim's activities on
the Russian front in 1941.
   Bronfman said his group gave the Soviets a list of 50,000 names
of suspected Nazi war criminals that were found in newly
declassified U.S. government files. He said the information was
passed on directly to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
