<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Hatred     05-15 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Hatred,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Day of Hatred' Planned To Recall Khmer Rouge Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian authorities plan nationwide
marches during a ``Day of Hatred'' commemorating the massacres by
the former Khmer Rouge regime.
   The Vietnamese-backed communist government said the ``Day of
Hatred'' would be Friday and called on the people to make posters
condemning ``the savage crimes'' of the Khmer Rouge.
   ``Pledge to turn hatred into revolutionary activities in
building strong villages and communes, in building the armed
forces, and in intensifying attacks on the enemy to protect the
peaceful life of the people,'' the government said in a directive
broadcast by the official radio station over the weekend.
   It said the posters will be carried in processions to rally
points where tribute will be paid to the victims of the Khmer Rouge.
   The Khmer Rouge, a radical communist guerrilla group, defeated
the U.S.-backed Cambodian government in the spring of 1975 and
forced the evacaution of the country's cities, making the residents
go into rural areas to work. Millions of Cambodians were killed by
the Khmer Rouge or died of starvation and disease.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978, ousting the Khmer Rouge
and establishing another communist government.
   The government directive said the Khmer Rouge is attempting to
regain power by intensifying psychological warfare in the villages
and sabotaging peace efforts between Prime Minister Hun Sen and
Prince Norodom Sihanouk, leader of a resistance coalition that
includes the Khmer Rouge.
   It said that in the capital of Phnom Penh, a ceremony will be
held Friday at the former Tuol Sleng high school where 20,000
people purportedly were massacred. The building is now a ``museum
of genocide'' with photographs of thousands of victims and displays
of instruments of torture.
</TEXT>
