<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Families,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Cries With Families</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The usually stoic Kentucky state medical
examiner couldn't fight back the tears as he told relatives of
people killed in a fiery church bus accident that they shouldn't
view the bodies.
   Before beginning his examination of the bodies that were piled
atop one another in the charred yellow church bus inside a Kentucky
National Guard armory, Dr. George Nichols went to the Holiday Inn
to speak to about 60 family members and friends who had made the
trip to help identify the dead.
   ``I want to tell them that the picture ... of their children in
that room is not what they have in their memories or wallet,''
Nichols told reporters before he left.
   But Nichols was moved as he met with the grieving in the motel's
banquet room, away from reporters.
   ``He was even crying along with everyone else,'' said a friend
to the parents of one of the victims. ``He's a very sensitive man
as far as that goes.''
   At least 27 people were killed when the bus was struck head-on
Saturday night by a pickup truck traveling in the wrong lane of
Interstate 71. The group was returning from an outing at Kings
Island amusement park north of Cincinnati.
   Ministers and Red Cross personnel were on hand Sunday to help
comfort and counsel the family members, some crying and others
stone-faced as if in disbelief.
   ``They're in shock,'' said Steve Watkins, youth minister at
Ghent Baptist Church, located about five miles from the accident
site. ``That's all I can say.''
   ``We're counseling and organizing the families to gather
information,'' said Marshall N. Eastham, a state police chaplain.
   ``The people are taking it as well as can be expected,'' said
Glenn Grubbs, a member of Radcliff First Assembly of God, where
most of the victims attended church. ``We're all still Christians.
   ``There's been a lot of praying and talking and grieving.''
   He said one of his friends ``lost his entire family (in the
accident). Obviously he's broken-hearted, but his faith is not
shaken.''
   The Rev. W. Don Tennison, pastor of the 600-member church, said
that some of his members were ``clinging to the hope that their
child is somewhere.''
   Tennison, whose son was on the trip but was unharmed, said he
was there to ``provide friendship, support and probably help them
work through some of the grief. It's going to take some time.''
   ``Everybody is in a state of shock, but they have a belief in
God to keep them going,'' said Tennison, who has been at the church
for about 10 years.
   ``We've been knocked down, but not knocked out.''
</TEXT>
