<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Shooting, 3d Ld-Writethru, a0815,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Gunmen Open Fire On Pub Patrons, Kill Three</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info-changes from 3d graf to end, caller asserting
responsibility, British minister and Sinn Fein denounce killings.
No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen entered a pub as
diners were finishing lunch Sunday and opened fire on the crowd,
killing three people and wounding six before fleeing in a
commandeered taxi, police and witnesses said.
   Ten people were taken to hospitals, six with gunshot wounds and
four suffering from shock, according to police.
   An anonymous telephone caller told the British Broadcasting
Corp. that the attack on the tavern patronized by Roman Catholics
was carried out by the Protestant Action Force.
   But a spokesman at BBC's Belfast office said the caller did not
give a recognized code used by the extremist Protestant Action
Force and the assertion could not be confirmed.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed and
predominantly Catholic Irish Republican Army, blamed the attack on
Protestant militants.
   The Avenue Bar on Union Street was preparing to close at 2:30
p.m. when the gunmen rang the bell and were admitted through the
electronically operated door, police said.
   Witnesses, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there were
about 20 people in the bar when the gunmen entered and appeared to
be looking for someone.
   ``A guy came in and took his time looking around and then
started shooting,'' one witness said. ``Then the other one came in
behind him and started shooting at people. It was just
indiscriminate; people were trying to dive for cover but they had
no chance.''
   Police said two people died at the scene and the third was
pronounced dead on arrival at a hospital. Moments after the
shooting, three priests arrived to administer last rites to the
dead.
   The gunmen had hijacked a taxi in the Protestant Shankill Road
area just before the attack and afterward drove off in the
direction of Shankill Road.
   Police and troops rushed into the area around the pub and set up
roadblocks. An army helicopter hovered above.
   Local people said the victims were from Unity Flats, Ballymurphy
and North Queen Street, all Catholic districts.
   The attack, the first of its kind in years in Belfast, fueled
fears of reprisals in the sectarian warfare that has ravaged this
predominantly Protestant British province.
   Tom King, Britain's secreatry for Northern Ireland, called the
killings a ``revolting outrage.'' Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams
said the attack was ``an attempt at mass murder.''
   Both men appealed for calm.
   ``There is no place in a civilized society for people as
depraved as these killers and that holds true for anybody who has
ever raised a gun in Northern Ireland in pursuit of sectarian or
political ends,'' King said.
   ``One thing Northern Ireland does not need now is talk of
retaliation and revenge. Good sense and restraint are what is
needed.''
   Adams said, ``The area is very tense and local people are very
angry. I appeal for calm and discipline.''
   The Protestant Action Force is an offshoot of the Ulster
Volunteer Force. Both organizations are illegal.
   The IRA is fighting to unite Northern Ireland, where Protestants
outnumber Catholics 3-2, with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic
of Ireland.
</TEXT>
