<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BirdSeries     05-15 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bird Series,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Team Wins World Series Of Birding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a hundred bird watchers spotted
a record number of species in the fifth annual World Series of
Birding, despite the adverse effects of a cold, wet spring on
migrations.
   The Zeiss Team, a New Jersey group led by Peter Dunne of
Bernardsville, spotted 200 species to beat 27 other teams from the
United States and Great Britain and capture the silver Urner-Stone
Cup.
   The bird watchers covered prime spots throughout the New
Jersey's marshes, woodlands and shores from midnight Friday to
midnight Saturday.
   Some teams traveled more than 400 miles during the contest,
which started at the Pequannock watershed about 40 miles northwest
of New York City and ending in the Cape May region in the south,
the state's best spot for night watching, said Paul Kerlinger,
director of the Cape May Bird Observatory.
   Dunne, who created the competition and was a member of the first
winning team, said this year's event was marred by a blustery
spring that slowed migrating patterns. Last year's winning team
spotted 205 species.
   ``There were no birds,'' Dunne said Sunday. ``It was silent
spring. It was cold and wet and birds just don't like those
conditions.''
   Dunne said the key to his team's success was that it ``just got
the meat and potatoes birds,'' including clutches of warblers and
kingfishers.
   Despite the poor spring, Kerlinger said contestants spotted a
combined total of 254 species, the best ever. The most striking
sighting was that of a sooty shearwater, an ocean bird rarely seen
from land, spotted off Cape May, he said.
   The obstacles weren't all natural. This year's runnerup, the
Woolrich-International Council for Bird Preservation from Britain,
sat through a two-hour delay on the New Jersey Turnpike during the
competition. They managed to spot 194 species.
   The event raised nearly $80,000 in pledges to conservation
groups, said Tom Gilmore, director of the New Jersey Audobon
Society.
</TEXT>
