<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 2ndLd-Writethru a0847 05-15 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0847,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Mass for 1.5 Million Amid Massive Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 14th graf ``He spoke...'' to UPDATE
with pope speaking to intellectuals and businessmen before retiring
for night. Pickup 15th graf pvs ``Although the...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II celebrated the largest Mass
of his South American tour Sunday with security provided by 20,000
soldiers and police after rebels set off explosions that plunged
parts of Lima into darkness.
   The pope later denounced the violence, poverty and other ills
that he said made Peruvian society seem like it was ``mined from
within.''
   An estimated 1.5 million people gathered in a park on the
outskirts of Lima, the nation's capital, for the outdoor Mass.
Hundreds of armed soldiers in full battle dress patrolled just
below the altar while helicopters flew overhead.
   The multitude chanted its welcome to the pontiff, greeting him
with a sea of yellow-and-white papal flags.
   John Paul, wearing white and gold vestments, appealed in his
homily for the building of a ``civilization of love.''
   ``A civilization, which, resting on this foundation of love for
the person who is near us _ our neighbor _ will transform ... the
whole world,'' he said.
   In an altar ceremony before the Mass, John Paul officially
closed the Fifth Marian Eucharistic Congress, a week-long meeting
of leading clergy from Venezuela, Colombia, Panama, Ecuador, Peru
and Bolivia.
   The government news agency ANDINA reported that 3,327 people
were picked up by security forces in Lima in connection with the
pope's visit. It said they were detained ``on suspicion'' but gave
no other details.
   Officials said insurgents were responsible for four dynamite
blasts in Lima Saturday night shortly after John Paul flew in from
Bolivia.
   No one was injured in the explosions. One was set off close to a
bullfighting ring near a central square where the pope consecrated
a statue of the Virgin Mary.
   Rebels also bombed towers and power-relay stations in the Andes
mountains east of Lima Saturday night, causing brief blackouts in
the capital.
   Guerrilla violence by leftist groups has claimed more than
10,000 lives in the 1980s.
   After the Mass, the pope addressed Peru's Roman Catholic
bishops. He said Peruvian society often seemed ``mined from within
by an unjustified eclipse in the required respect for human
dignity.''
   He spoke of a ``blind and insensitive violence to repeated calls
to reconciliation,'' widening poverty, drug trafficking, and the
growth of sects and persistence of doctrines ``that create
confusion among the faithful and attack the unity of the church.''
   Before retiring for the night in the Vatican Embassy, the pope
spoke to a group of intellectuals and businessmen. He told the
intellectuals not to confuse the church's mission with ``mere
earthly goals or political action.''
   He admonished businessmen to improve their workers' living
standards but also defended them saying: ``Often it is forgotten
that you are men who confront risks ... and contribute to
technological advance.''
   Although the pope did not directly mention the problem of
guerrilla activity at the Mass, he did refer to a bloody prison
uprising by the Maoist Shining Path rebel group in a taped message
to inmates broadcast by Peruvian radio Sunday.
   The army killed more than 250 guerrillas in putting down the
revolt two years ago, and John Paul said, ``I know of the painful
tensions which have cost lamentable blood quotas, and I know of
your sufferings and needs, which in spite of noble and generous
efforts on the part of authorities, have not been overcome.''
   Troops and police in riot gear sealed off downtown Lima and
guarded public buildings and hotels.
   Heavy security was particularly evident when the pope paid a
morning call on President Alan Garcia in the government palace.
   As Garcia, a populist who has halted virtually all payment of
Peru's $15 million dollar foreign debt, led John Paul through a
garden, they passed two armored personnel carriers, soldiers
carrying Israeli-made Uzi submachine guns and a special
anti-terrorist team in red berets.
   From the palace, John Paul traveled in his vehicle, known as the
popemobile, to the Campo San Miquel Mass site, passing thousands of
cheering and waving people along the six-mile motorcade route.
   The pope was scheduled to leave Peru on Monday morning and fly
to Paraguay, last stop on his South American tour that began in
Uruguay May 7. He was due to return to Rome on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
