<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 2153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-DanceFestival     05-15 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance Festival,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYC Ballet's Festival a Smash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Ballet's three-week, $3.5
million American Music Festival, which concluded Sunday, presented
an array of new works of remarkably high quality, any of which
could enter the company's repertoire.
   The festival _ with old ballets and 21 new ones by 18
choreographers, all danced to American music _ has been a smashing
success, surely greater than the company expected. The New York
State Theater has been full for most performances and audiences
have been enthusiastic.
   The orchestra's playing has not always been top drawer. Of
course, they had 21 unfamiliar pieces of music _ five of them
commissioned for the festival _ to perform in three weeks, and much
of the music was modern and difficult.
   Dancers have looked outstanding throughout, even in pieces that
might have been allowed to slide through, like George Balanchine's
1954 ``Western Symphony.''
   The quality of the new ballets has been remarkably high. Since
Balanchine's death in 1983 it has been obvious the company needs to
add new works by a variety of choreographers. A festival, bringing
in a lot of new works in a short time, has proved a splendid idea.
Even choreographers who used Balanchine's neo-classic dance
vocabulary didn't create Balanchine clones.
   No premiere that we have seen couldn't enter the repertoire.
``Barber Violin Concerto,'' by Peter Martins, which used a couple
from the New York City Ballet and two guest artists from the world
of modern dance, was our favorite. Martins, who directs the company
along with Jerome Robbins, choreographed four of the new ballets.
   Of the five dances we saw for the first time on the final
weekend, we most liked ``Behind the china dogs,'' a highly original
ballet with distinctive, elliptical lighting, choreographed by
William Forsythe, artistic director of the Frankfurt Ballet since
1984. Forsythe chose well-muscled dancers. Solos looked crafted
specially for each soloist.
   Music was composed by Leslie Stuck on an electronic emulator,
which allowed ``a pack of dogs to jam with two string quartets and
a bowling ball.'' Some of the music and movement was jazzy and
amusing, unlike that of most of the other new ballets, which were
very serious.
   Violette Verdy, ballerina in the company from 1958 to 1977,
choreographed ``Set of Seven'' to 19th century Romantic-style piano
music by Mary Jean van Appledorn, head of the music department at
Texas Tech University. We liked the music better than the dance.
   Miriam Mahdaviani, who joined the New York City Ballet in 1980,
created a notable dance, ``The Newcomers,'' to music by David
Diamond. It's in neo-classic style and keeps a charming sense of
balance even when patterns aren't actually symmetrical. Five
soloists are introduced at unpredictable intervals through the
ballet instead of making the usual measured entrances. Holly Hynes
used striking colors for the soloists' leotards, contrasting with
the corps de ballet in white.
   Martins choreographed ``Tea-Rose'' in flowing balletic ballroom
style to five George Gershwin melodies that have never had lyrics.
Michael Tilson Thomas played piano and conducted. The final tune,
``Promenade,'' sounds familiar because Fred Astaire and Ginger
Rogers danced to it in ``Shall We Dance.''
   Martins also choreographed ``Black & White'' to music by Michel
Torke, in which eccentric hand gestures looked gimmicky, but then
this perception may have been caused by the viewer's ballet burnout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
