<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 2208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Helicopter     05-15 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Helicopter,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wreckage Of U.S. Helicopter Located in Persian Gulf, Bodies
Recovered</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two U.S. Navy pilots and
the wreckage of their helicopter were located in the southern
Persian Gulf on Sunday, the Pentagon said, nearly a month after
they disappeared during U.S.-Iranian clashes.
   The destroyer USS Merrill, two chartered tugboats and a seagoing
crane were sighted off the emirate of Sharjah, indicating an effort
to retrieve the wreckage was under way, maritime salvage experts
said.
   In Washington, Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman,
confirmed the wreckage of the Marine Corps AH-1 Cobra was located
Sunday.
   He said the bodies of the two pilots _ Capt. Kenneth Hill, 33,
of Thomasville, N.C., and Capt. Stephen Leslie, 30, of New Bern,
N.C. _ were recovered.
   They were the only American casualties in the fighting April 18,
when U.S. naval forces destroyed two Iranian oil platforms and sank
or disabled six naval craft. Iran said at the time that its forces
shot down the helicopter.
   Tehran said 44 Iranians were killed during the clash.
   The fighting began after U.S. forces earlier that day destroyed
two Iranian oil platforms in retaliation for a mine explosion in
the gulf four days before that damaged the USS Samuel Roberts and
wounded 10 sailors aboard.
   The Navy had officially called off the search for the helicopter
and declared the men killed in action. Memorial services later were
held for the two Americans in Jacksonville, N.C., where their unit
was based.
   The wreckage was located by a chartered salvage tugboat, said
the salvage experts, speaking on condition of anonymity. The
wreckage was found in the general location where the raids
occurred, they said.
   The helicopter was on an evening patrol serving as backup for
U.S. combat ships the day it disappeared. It was dispatched from
the cruiser USS Wainwright.
   In their last dispatch, the pilots radioed that they had
detected hostile radar tracking their aircraft.
   The Iranians on April 23 claimed on their state-run radio that
their Revolutionary Guards retrieved the some of the wreckage of
the helicopter and brought it ashore.
   The death of the two men brought to 46 the number of Americans
killed in and near the Persian Gulf in the past year. The figure
includes 37 killed in an erroneous Iraqi missile strike on the
frigate Stark May 17 last year. The others were killed in
helicopter crashes.
</TEXT>
