<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p Jackson DukakisEachFailToScoreMajorityOfStateDemocrats
  05-15 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Jackson, Dukakis Each Fail To Score Majority Of State Democrats</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRBANKS, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither Jesse Jackson nor Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis had a clear majority of Alaska's Democratic
delegates Sunday following the state party's weekend convention.
   ``It was a negotiated settlement, is what it was,'' said Bob
Speed, executive director of the state Democratic Party. ``There
were two votes taken and both were very close. It had to be
negotiated from the standpoint of who got how many delegates.''
   When the dust settled, Jackson had seven delegates and Dukakis
had six. Four delegates were undecided.
   While Jackson won a strong majority of the delegates at the
Alaska Democratic Party's precinct and district caucuses in March
and April, Dukakis had a strong showing among the previously
undecided at the weekend convention.
   Many of those said they migrated to the Dukakis camp because he
is the national front-runner.
   ``I think the results represent a true picture of the closeness
of the Democratic race in Alaska,'' said Gov. Steve Cowper, a
Dukakis backer.
</TEXT>
