<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CostaRica-Refugees     05-15 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Refugees,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boatload of Nicaraguan Refugees Arrives in Costa Rica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan government boat
carrying 122 men, women and children docked at Limon on Sunday and
the captain and all but two of those on board declared themselves
refugees, a security official said.
   Captain Felipe Alvarado Castillo told Costa Rican authorities
the boat left Nicaragua's Caribbean port of Bluefields several days
ago, Carlos Jimenez, the security official, told The Associated
Press by telephone.
   He quoted the captain as saying the boat left to deliver food to
Corn Island, but that the passengers had decided to seek asylum.
   The refugees included 28 women, 35 men and 57 children, Jimenez
said.
   Jimenez said the boat had the identification number 20-INRA, but
he did not say how large it was. He did not say how long the boat
was at sea.
   It was not clear if the boat was stolen, taken with permission
for a trip to Corn Island and then diverted to Limon, 70 miles east
of San Jose, or obtained in some other way. Limon is 150 miles
southeast of Bluefields.
   Jimenez said two passengers, identified as Patricia Delgado and
Julio Antonio Vargas, were Nicaraguan government officials and told
authorities they wanted to return to Nicaragua. There was no
indication of what government jobs they held.
   During April and the first week of May more than 1,000
Nicaraguan refugees arrived in Costa Rica, an apparent increase
over previous weeks, rural guard officials say. Most walk across
this country's northern border at various points, particularly in
the northwest.
   More than 60,000 Nicaraguans have been registered as refugees in
Costa Rica since U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras began fighting
in 1981 to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government. An
estimated 50,000 others live in Costa Rica illegally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
