<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government calls it ``zero tolerance,''
but industry and civil liberties groups have begun to question
whether ``overkill'' isn't an equally accurate description of the
policy under which luxury yachts and other private property is
being seized in the battle against drugs.
   In the latest episode, the U.S. Coast Guard confiscated on
Saturay the yacht Monkey Business, the charter vessel that once
ferried presidential contender Gary Hart and model Donna Rice to
the Bahamas, after officers said they found 1 gram _ or one
twenty-eighth of an ounce _ of marijuana aboard.
   Only days earlier, the Coast Guard seized the $2.5 million
yacht, Ark Royal, on grounds that one-tenth of an ounce of
marijuana was aboard. No one was arrested in either case.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress are alarmed that a recent
court ruling will strip away two centuries of legal protection for
their official activities, exposing them to lawsuits for monetary
damages.
   The House legal staff notes that courts have previously chipped
away at the immunity lawmakers were granted in the Constitution to
protect them from suits resulting from their activities on the
floor and in committee.
   But in a ruling involving Rep. Don Sundquist, the legal experts
say, an appellate court has now left members of Congress without a
wider immunity granted throughout the nation's history by federal
courts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just two years ago, the Congressional Budget
Office's economic forecasts ruled Capitol Hill, and its decisions
could force the president to cut billions of dollars in federal
spending.
   But the Congress has stripped the office of important powers,
left it without a permanent director for more than a year, and
exposed the officially non-partisan agency to charges of political
tampering.
   ``CBO is disintegrating,'' said Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa.,
chairman of the House Budget Committee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II's scheduled visit to
Paraguay has magnified a split between the 34-year-old
authoritarian government of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner and the
increasingly critical Roman Catholic clergy.
   The pontiff was scheduled to arrive Monday for a 57-hour visit
to this overwhelmingly Catholic country, the last stop on a 12-day
pilgrimage that has taken him to Uruguay, Bolivia and Peru.
   Perhaps the most politically sensitive stop, the visit has
spotlighted deteriorating ties between the church and the rightist
government, whose members often describe clerical critics as
communists and subversives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans view Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
nearly as favorably as they do President Reagan, and Gorbachev
out-polls Reagan among college-educated Americans, a Media
General-Associated Press poll has found.
   Less than a month before the superpower leaders meet in Moscow,
the national survey found broad support for Reagan's handling of
U.S.-Soviet relations and a high positive view of Reagan generally.
   But while 59 percent of those polled held favorable opinions of
Reagan, virtually as many _ 54 percent _ expressed a positive view
of Gorbachev, the poll found. The split was within the margin of
sampling error.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trickle of Democratic Party leaders
supporting presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis has turned
into a steady stream, while movement to back the candidacy of Jesse
Jackson has all but stopped.
   In the weeks since his make-or-break victory in the Wisconsin
primary, the Massachusetts governor has picked up support from 68
of the party's ``super delegates,'' while Jackson has gained just
four, according to a survey by The Associated Press.
   In all, Dukakis has 1,608 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, of whom 202 are super delegates _ the 643 party leaders
and politicians whose titles won them seats as delegates. Dukakis
is now more than three-quarters of the way to the 2,081 delegates
needed to win the party's presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conventional wisdom would have you believe
that Democrat Michael Dukakis must choose a Southerner as his vice
presidential running mate and Republican George Bush must balance
the ticket with a conservative.
   But there are a dozen choices that fit neither bill, and history
indicates the nominees may turn to someone the handicappers
consider a long shot, or didn't consider at all.
   Bush was an 11th hour choice by Reagan in 1980. Lyndon Johnson
was written off as a potential running mate for John F. Kennedy in
1960. Spiro Agnew was unknown until Richard Nixon tapped him in
1968 and Bob Dole was at the top of nobody's list in 1976 _ except
Gerald Ford's.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bud Clark, Portland's exuberant
barkeep-turned-mayor, expects to defy political odds once more by
winning re-election despite a stormy first term.
   Clark shocked the city four years ago when he stepped out of his
Goose Hollow Inn and mounted a grass-roots campaign to unseat
incumbent Frank Ivancie, who had dismissed the newcomer's chances.
   In his first two years in office, however, Clark faced a series
of crises, mostly involving the city Police Bureau. Two police
chiefs resigned and Clark fired a third.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHERNOBYL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public fear of nuclear power and
unexpected criticism from the press suddenly have made Soviet
officials strikingly defensive about their efforts to deal with the
effects of the Chernobyl disaster.
   Comments by some officials during a conference on the medical
effects of the accident and a tour of the mammoth Chernobyl nuclear
power plant last week suggested they are worried that public
opposition could halt development of nuclear power in the Soviet
Union.
   The April 26, 1986, explosion and fire at the Chernobyl plant's
No. 4 reactor killed at least 31 people and released a cloud of
radioactive material that eventually circled the globe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The monkeys at Paignton Zoological and Botanical
Gardens are soon to get new, improved housing, thanks to a $750,000
bequest from a woman who loved their company.
   For decades, elderly women have been leaving their fortunes to
animal charities like the Cats Protection League, the Donkey
Sanctuary or zoos like Paignton in southwest England.
   This week the Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals received the largest gift in its 164-year history _ $5.15
million from an 80-year-old widow who lived with her cat, Pussy.
Even in a nation of pet owners, charities say, such women shine.
</TEXT>
