<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Steel-Taconite Bjt   05-15 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel-Taconite, Bjt,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iron Range Taconite Industry Facing Rare Labor Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVELETH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The steel industry's hard-earned rebound
is reviving the taconite mines of the Mesabi Iron Range, where
skilled workers who were banished by layoffs years ago are suddenly
in short supply.
   The rare labor shortage has emerged as a call for help goes out
to ex-taconite workers who fled as far away as Arizona and Florida
during the industry's seven-year recession.
   They often are torn between remaining in their new jobs or
returning to northeastern Minnesota, where family ties run as deep
as the mine pits that helped fight two world wars by supplying ore
to the nation's steelmakers.
   ``People want to come back home,'' said Tom Gilpin, placement
interviewer for the Minnesota Department of Jobs and Training in
Virginia, Minn. ``But I guess we've been burned so many times up
here, some of them just don't believe it's going to last.''
   Gilpin, who is taking applications for jobs at LTV Steel Mining
Co. in Hoyt Lakes, said some former employees who were called back
to work rejected the opportunity because they are secure in their
new jobs. But most miners _ some laid off for up to five years _
have returned.
   ``I'm glad to see it,'' said Ed Logan, 32, of Palo, who was
called back to work at LTV after being laid off nearly five years.
``I didn't think I'd ever get called back, but I guess I just kept
hanging in.''
   Logan said he eked out a living on the Iron Range working a
variety of jobs during his extended layoff. Being single helped him
avoid the fate of some of his married friends, many of whom were
forced to leave the area, he said.
   The decline of the taconite mines in recent years followed the
slide in steel production. Taconite is a flint-like rock containing
a low-grade iron ore that is extracted and converted into pellets.
The pellets are then shipped to steel plants for smelting.
   Iron Range taconite production peaked at 56 million tons in
1979, and fell as low as 23 million tons in 1982. Industry experts
estimate 40 percent of the $2.5 billion worth of mining equipment
in Minnesota, the nation's largest producer of iron ore, was idle
in recent years.
   Taconite production in 1988 is projected at about 40 million
tons, up from 31 million tons in 1987.
   Al France, executive director of the Lake Superior Industrial
Bureau in Duluth, said the six working taconite plants on the Iron
Range currently employ about 5,000 people, about 500 more than a
year ago, but well below the 1979 high of 15,000.
   Eldon Kirsch, District 33 president of the United Steelworkers
of America in Duluth, said the rebound has been made possible by
wage concessions and job consolidation.
   ``It's better now than it has been since 1980,'' Kirsch said.
``But that doesn't mean we have all our people back.
   ``Plants that operated with 500 in the past are operating with
300,'' he added. ``Where there were 2,000 workers, now 1,300 are
employed.''
   Most of the current hiring is taking place at the LTV plant in
Hoyt Lakes, where three shifts aim to produce 8.2 million tons of
taconite pellets this year, and at Eveleth Mines, where a second
production line is scheduled to begin July 1 after being idle since
1982.
   ``We're wide open right now for the first time since 1976,''
said Jim Kozar of LTV, president of Local 4108 of the United
Steelworkers of America.
   Kozar, Kirsch, Gilpin and others say there is an abundance of
unskilled labor but a shortage of electricians with mining
experience. Most Iron Range taconite producers ended apprenticeship
programs for electricians in the downturn and many of the laid-off
electricians have landed secure jobs in other places that they are
afraid to leave, they said.
   ``We're losing a certain number of them,'' said Bob Raich,
personnel director at Eveleth. ``The supply of technical and craft
people would be very, very short right now if you were to start up
a mining operation here.''
   Kozar said the scaled-back mining wage for electricians of about
$11.50 an hour isn't helping to attract the top unexperienced
electricians.
   Gilpin, the state labor official, said he has taken 3,200
applications for jobs at LTV, mostly from unskilled workers. He
said he has placed about 200 applicants.
   The ``off-the-street'' hiring is rare because it means the
company has exhausted its reserve of laid-off workers, Gilpin said.
   ``This is the first time they have come to us and said, `We need
your help,''' Gilpin said.
   Stan Daniels, president of Local 6860 of the United Steelworkers
of America in Eveleth, said it's a shock to see the mining
companies advertising in newspapers for workers and hiring
unskilled workers off the street. But it's a welcome sight because
it means that laid-off miners have had their shot at returning to
work, he said.
   ``Some of them have moved out, sold their places and they are
staying where they're at,'' Daniels said. ``But to others, there's
no place like home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
