<FILEID>AP-NR-05-15-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Steel Bjt   05-15 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel, Bjt,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Rides The Crest Of Demand Wave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After drifting through the shoal water of the
1980s and sometimes running aground, American steelmakers are happy
to have deep water finally under the bow.
   But where economic currents will carry them in the coming
quarters is an open question.
   ``Business is booming,'' said industry analyst Charles Bradford
of the investment firm Merrill Lynch & Co. ``Nobody sees anything
in their business that shows any sign of weakness, but they're all
worried about it because of what they hear from their economists.''
   The industry's prospects will dominate discussions at the
American Iron and Steel Institute annual convention on Wednesday
and Thursday in Washington, D.C.
   A combination of excess production capacity and slack orders
hammered the industry between 1981 and 1987: steelmakers closed
plants capable of making 30 million tons of steel per year,
eliminated about 220,000 jobs and sustained losses totaling about
$12 billion.
   In the process, they modernized remaining plants and bargained
new contracts, two steps which by some estimates halved the labor
needed to make an average ton of steel. The industry also persuaded
the Reagan administration to limit steel imports through quotas
negotiated with 31 countries.
   Now some plants are turning away orders ``because they don't
want to stretch out delivery times too long. Your customers tend to
get aggravated,'' said Wayne Atwell, an analyst for Goldman, Sachs.
   March shipments of 7.7 million tons were the most since June
1981 and were up 21 percent from March 1986. Previous estimates
that 1988 shipments would total 70 million tons could be
outstripped by 10 million tons.
   Some users can't buy enough metal.
   ``Just about everybody I talk to says they could sell more steel
if they could get it,'' Atwell said.
   USX Chairman David Roderick claims his company, the largest U.S.
steel producer, is now so competitive it could export more ``if we
had more product available.''
   Bradford doubts export opportunities are that bright, but none
of the analysts suggest that too many plants have been closed or
that the approximately 170,000 blue- and white-collar steelworkers
left on the job are not enough.
   ``If anything, people think there still should be more''
production capacity cut, Bradford said.
   ``The steel industry...lost an absolute fortune over the last
four or five or six years,'' Atwell said. ``They had to raise
prices to make a reasonable profit. If part of that means shutting
down capacity...to meet normal demand but giving up some business
at peak demand, then that's realistic.''
   Atwell said prices fell 15 percent over the five years after
their 1981 peak. Various estimates say prices now recovered from a
third to half of the decline, and Atwell expects prices to climb
another 4 percent to 5 percent this year.
   The industry turnaround, bolstered by the weakening of the
dollar, helped Bethlehem Steel Corp., for example, post a 1987
profit of $174 million, its first annual profit since 1981.
   The third-largest producer had lost more than $2 billion in the
interim and warned investors it might join second-ranked LTV Corp.
and smaller Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. and Sharon Steel Corp.
in Chapter 11 reorganization.
   LTV, after losing $4.5 billion from 1983 to 1986, showed a
profit of $502 million last year and $163 million in the 1988 first
quarter. This month the company unveiled a tentative plan for
settling its $6 billion in debts and emerging from bankruptcy
protection.
   ``I see no reason at this point for this upturn in steel
producing fortunes to change in the months and the quarters
ahead,'' Roderick told USX shareholders this month.
   A general economic recession seems to be the industry's largest
worry. Many economists expect a downturn by late 1988 or in the
next year or so.
   Several analysts also are concerned large steel inventories
could lead to a drop in orders, weaker prices and profit problems.
   Peter F. Marcus of the investment firm PaineWebber says the
extraordinarily high production levels cited by National
Association of Purchasing Managers surveys are ``overwhelming
evidence'' that steel users are building inventory.
   Bradford cites the Steel Service Center Institute's recent
report of a record 6.8 million tons in inventory in March. The
institute's 400 members handle one-third of the nation's steel.
   But Andrew Sharkey, president of the institute, noted that daily
shipping rats also were at record levels.
   ``The market ... fundamentals are still pretty solid,'' he said.
</TEXT>
